<HEADLINE> Bosnian President Postpones Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- It seems not appropriate for
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic to visit Egypt at present, the
charge d'affaires of Bosnian embassy was quoted by Egypt's Middle
East News Agency (MENA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was made by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
and contacts are underway between Cairo and Sarajevo to set the
date for the visit, which is to take place most likely by the end
of this month, said the Bosnian diplomat.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that the present time is not appropriate for this
visit, taking into consideration the conditions in Kosovo
(Yugoslavia)," he told MENA.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between the Yugoslav forces and ethnic Albanian armed
groups escalated over the past weeks in Kosovo. Hundreds have died
and thousands others been displaced since Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic launched a crackdown on February 28 against the
ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting to wrest
Kosovo province from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
In a developing confrontation between Milosevic and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, the 16-nation alliance has
threatened air strikes against Yugoslavia if Milosevic fails to
end military action against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the main republic of
Yugoslavia. Ninety percent of its 2 million people are ethnic
Albanians and 10 percent, Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on September 23 demanded withdrawal
of more Serb troops from Kosovo, allowing humanitarian aid to
refugees and opening up serious talks with the secessionists on
the restoration of self-rule for the ethnic Albanians-dominated
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
