<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Minister on China's Fiscal Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 13 (Xinhua ) -- Chinese Vice Minister of
Finance Lou Jiwei said Tuesday that the Chinese government has
adopted a positive fiscal policy in the face of the Asian
financial crisis and has achieved good results.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the Seventh East Asian Economic Summit,
Lou said from the beginning of the Asian financial crisis the
Chinese government has pursued a policy to stabilize the exchange
rate of its currency and expand domestic demand for the benefit of
its own economy and the economy of the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Three months ago, it decided to add specific positive policies
to expand fiscal expenditure in a bid to ensure economic growth,
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the much-talked issue of the devaluation of the RMB, he said
despite mounting pressures, China has committed itself not to
devaluate its currency amid the regional turmoil.
</P>
<P>
China holds that devaluation could not increase its export, but
rather could start a new round of competitive devaluation in the
Asian region, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the RMB would harm Asian countries and the
people in the region who have already been hit by the Asian
financial crisis, he said. So China avoided to do so, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lou noted that some countries that had devaluated their
currencies competitively at the start of the crisis have taken
measures to expand their internal demands and as a result their
currencies appeared to start moving toward stability.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that countries badly hit by the Asian
crisis could get out of the mire through restructuring and reform
and that developed countries and international institutions
shoulder more responsibilities to bring the region out of the
crisis by taking emergency and effective measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
