<HEADLINE> Lukashenko Denounces Air Passage Permission for NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko Tuesday expressed "shock" over the readiness expressed
by several countries including Bulgaria and Romania to allow
passage for NATO aircraft to bomb Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Such permission signifies "conspiracy to the crimes being
prepared at the Balkans," the Interfax news agency quoted
Lukashenko as saying in Minsk.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of the former socialist countries put up their
people for a strike. Do the leaders have to humiliate themselves
and their people to such a degree to get into NATO, being
apprehensive that the European Union would reject them? Our Slav
unity is sacred! Suddenly it is all betrayed, stomped out," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Minsk's attitude toward these states that allowed NATO
air passage "has morally changed."
</P>
<P>
"Not only Belarus but Russia and Ukraine in future will make
pertinent conclusions with regard to their relations with these
countries," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
However, Lukashenko said he was firmly against the dispatch of
Belarussian volunteer units to Yugoslavia and the country's
constitution banned Belarussians from taking part in military
actions abroad.
</P>
<P>
"As a statesman and a president, I will fight for Yugoslavia
using my own methods," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, the Belarussian Foreign Ministry urged NATO to
discontinue preparations for air strikes in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis can be resolved only through full compliance with
U.N. Security Council resolutions on Kosovo by all parties. The
resolutions do not give NATO a mandate to use force," the ministry
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Use of force against a sovereign country without U.N. Security
Council authorization is flagrant violation of the U.N. Charter,
contravenes the basic legal principles of international relations
and undermines the security and confidence system on the European
continent," Interfax quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
"NATO's military intervention in an internal conflict will
aggravate the confrontation in Kosovo rather than remove its
causes. NATO's strikes against targets in Yugoslavia will amount
to new hostilities in the Balkans resulting inevitably in chaos
and loss of civilian life, long-term destabilization of Europe,
new flows of refugees and other unpredictable consequences," the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
