<HEADLINE> Mubarak Assured of Fastness of Aswan High Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has been assured of the fastness of Aswan High Dam on the Nile
river despite of the unprecedented high water in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was told by Minister of Public Works and Water
Resources Mahmoud Abu Zeid Tuesday that the dam's structure was
not affected by the rising water. He was inspecting the dam and
inaugurating new power stations at the reservoir behind the dam,
the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and some other
cabinet members, Mubarak reviewed the Toshka emergency spillway,
used to discharge excessive water in the Lake Nasser behind the
dam when needed.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zeid said since its erection in 1971, the dam has protected
Egypt, which used to suffer periodic floodings and droughts from
the Nile, from six devastating floods and 10 very low flows. It
was the dam that prepared the grounds for a stable agriculture in
Egypt, for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
The water in the man-made Lake Nasser, which stretches 500
kilometers up the Nile, rose to a record level of 181.15 meters on
Monday. Excess water was being channel to the Toshka canal to
irrigate a swath of the desert to the northwest of the dam.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time since the dam was completed that the
Nile water was diverted. The first was in 1996 when the water
behind the dam reached 178 meters, a record high.
</P>
<P>
The current diversion period began early September when the
water rose upon the dam's safety level of 175 meters.
</P>
<P>
Africa's longest river of 1,670 kilometers, the Nile runs
south-north through several countries before pouring into the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
It has an average annual flow of 84 billion cubic meters, with
80 percent of the volume concentrated in the flood season from
August through October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
