<HEADLINE> Finland Satisfied with Political Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish government issued
a statement Tuesday welcoming the new agreement over Kosovo crisis
struck between U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied that a political solution has been reached
over the Kosovo crisis. It is the determination of the
international community that has prompted such a solution,"
Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
She said that the door is already open for the implementation
of the U.N. Security Council Resolution 1199 as well as for Kosovo
refugees' return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
She also added that the Finnish government would discuss how to
participate and contribute its efforts in helping carry out the
agreement and ease situation in the troubled Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
NATO on Tuesday night authorized air strikes on Yugoslavia at
any time but gave Yugoslav government four days' grace to comply
with all U.N. demands which also include the free access of
international aid agencies in Kosovo and allow thousands of
refugees to go back home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
