<HEADLINE> Writethru: One Israeli Killed in Shooting Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli man was killed and
another one critically injured in a shooting incident Tuesday,
Israeli police said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred near Ora, a communal farm about five
kilometers west of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem police spokesman Shmuel Ben-Ruby said the victims
were bathing in a spring near Ora when shots were fired at
them. The assailants fled from the scene after the shooting and
their car was later found abandoned in the southern Jerusalem,
near the border with the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The assailants were Palestinian militants and Israeli police
and soldiers of the defense forces are conducting a manhunt for
the assailants.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Palestinan militant groups have carried out a
number of drive-by shootings in hoping of wrecking
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In August, two Jewish seminary students were shot and killed
outside the West Bank settlement of Yitzhar.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's shooting came two days before the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders were to meet in Washington to strike an
agreement on Israel's further troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Landau, Chairman of the Knesset (parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee, sharply criticized the shooting
incident, calling on Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu no to go
to Washington summit starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Meir Sheetrit, Knesset Coalition Chairman, said the the
incident should not be used to veto the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process must move forward without any conditions
and we must understand that some people want to destroy the
process," Sheetrit told the Israel Radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation on Target for Second Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Inflation has remained at the
British government's target level of 2.5 percent for the second
month running, increasing calls for the Bank of England to cut
interest rates further.
</P>
<P>
The underlying rate of inflation in September was unchanged
from August, according to the Office for National Statistics. The
headline rate of inflation which includes the cost of mortgages
dropped slightly by 0.1 percent to 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The retail inflation figures follow data released Monday
showing that the rise in prices of goods leaving factory gates is
at its lowest point for almost 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Factory gate prices are regarded as a valuable guide to the
long-term outlook for retail inflation and some commentators now
believe the figure may even fall below the government's target.
</P>
<P>
Barry Naisbitt, Abbey National spokesman, was quoted by a BBC
report as saying, "It's really very good news that inflation is
still right on target and suggesting that there isn't a great deal
of inflationary pressure in the U.K. economy at the moment."
</P>
<P>
Sheetal Radia of Standard and Poor's said, "I think the fact
that the headline inflation rate, which is the key for pay
settlements, has softened, is basically boding well for lower pay
rises in future. I think that's going to be supportive of the Bank
of England or the MPC cutting rates later this year."
</P>
<P>
World stock markets soared Monday partly in the hope of
interest rate cuts in leading economies, with the FTSE 100 Index
of leading shares posting its biggest ever daily points gain.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Bank of England cut interest rates by 0.25
percent to 7.25 percent, saying the international economic crisis
had become more of a risk to Britain's economy than domestic
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Some commentators claim the risk to the economy is now of
deflation, rather than inflation.
</P>
<P>
But while the inflation figures have given ammunition to the
so-called `doves' who favor rate cuts on the bank's Monetary
Policy Committee, analysts said that wages were still rising at
worrying levels.
</P>
<P>
Official wages figures had to be revised upwards recently as
pay settlements increased beyond expectations.
</P>
<P>
Julian Jessop, analyst at Nikko Europe, said, "There is clearly
deflation in some sectors of the economy, but the bank is
concentrating on wage rises."
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately the MPC wants to see more unemployment before it
is happy that inflation is under control," he said.
</P>
<P>
Several members of the MPC follow the view that a rise in
jobless figures would create a downwards pressure on wages,
keeping a tight lid on inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
