<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Gets Conditional Support from Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet Tuesday gave
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu the mandate to negotiate a deal
with the Palestinians in the coming U.S. summit, but linking it to
Palestinian security guarantees, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet secretary Danny Naveh said the ministers put support
behind Netanyahu as he is due to begin talks with Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat at Wye Plantation
in Maryland Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the cabinet's support was on conditions that the
Palestinians live up to their commitment and Israel's security
needs be met, Naveh said.
</P>
<P>
Gaps have been narrowed between Israel and the Palestinians on
the negotiations over the second Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank, but differences still remain, especially on the security
fields.
</P>
<P>
Even if the conditions are met during the U.S. summit and an
agreement on a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal is signed, the
National Religious Party (NRP) - the extreme rightist party in
Netanyahu's coalition - still needs to debate on its next move,
party officials said.
</P>
<P>
NRP has threatened to topple the government if it gives up 13
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians. But after Netanyahu
seemed to have decided to go his own way, the NRP said that it
will now see how the land would be ceded.
</P>
<P>
NRP Minister Shaul Yhalom said after the cabinet meeting that
if an agreement is signed in the coming talks his party will have
a debate and then decide if it will move forward to topple the
government. The party will see whether all the Jewish settlements
in the West Bank are unaffected by the agreement, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the cabinet meeting, the hardline Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon was unanimously approved foreign minister as
expected. He was appointed to the new post by Netanyahu last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sharon will, together with Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky, join Netanyahu
in the U.S. talks.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has reacted cautiously to the appointment of Sharon,
saying that it will deal with him as other Israeli foreign
ministers. 
</P>
