<HEADLINE> India, Mauritius Agree to Boost Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 13 ( Xinhua) -- India and Mauritius agreed
Tuesday to explore ways to upgrade political relations and give a
new dimension to bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during wide-ranging discussions
between visiting Mauritian Prime Minister Navinchandra Ramgoolam
and Indian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam arrived here earlier today for a two-day official
visit to the south Asian country, during which an agreement on
civil aviation would be signed between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Mauritian leader called on Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan and later held separate meetings with Home Minister L.
K. Advani, Defense Minister George Fernandes and Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to hold talks later with Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee on regional, international and mutual
concerns, which would be a follow-up of talks the two leaders had
when Vajpayee visited Mauritius last month.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam also met the opposition Congress President Sonia
Gandhi and will meet other Indian government leaders Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a ceremonial reception by Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee Tuesday, Ramgoolam told reporters that his visit
would further strengthen bilateral relations between the two
countries in political and economic spheres.
</P>
<P>
The visiting prime minister said that apart from receiving
technical assistance from India, his country would also explore
the possibilities of increasing trade and investment with India.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius, a member of the Indian Ocean Rim for Regional
Cooperation, is one of the leading investors in India and its
exports to India last year amounted to some 12.5 million U.S.
dollars while India's exports to the country was about 100 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
