<HEADLINE> Contact Group to Ponder Further Steps on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The international Contact Group
will meet within the next one or two days to consider further
steps over the latest agreements on Kosovo reached in Belgrade, a
Russian Foreign Ministry official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Russia wants the meeting to be held at the level of the
foreign ministries," said Vladimir Chizhov, director of the
Russian Foreign Ministry's Europe III Department.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, reached in Belgrade between Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke, was
"a very important step towards changing the situation for the
better," the Interfax news agency quoted Chizhov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A turning point has been reached. It makes no sense to discuss
the use of force now," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged NATO to cancel its decision on political consent to
the use of force against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The international community succeeded through "coordinated
actions and with Russia's active role," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that at a meeting with the Russian foreign and defense
ministers on October 4 in Belgrade, the Yugoslav leadership agreed
in principle to accept a civilian mission of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke enhanced these agreements, Chizhov said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir
Rakhmanin, welcoming the Milosevic-Holbrooke agreements, said he
was confident that Russia would take part in what he described as
the OSCE Observer Mission in Kosovo, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Chizhov said a resolution of the U.N. Security Council and a
decision of the OSCE Permanent Council are needed to send an
observer mission. It will take a few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
"A physical deployment of the mission is a matter of weeks," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
