<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Breakthrough Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan "warmly welcomes" the news of a breakthrough in efforts
to end the Kosovo crisis and he will send a mission to the region
in the coming days, a U.N. spokesman said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, U.N. spokesman, told a press conference, "It is
of paramount importance that both sides in Kosovo honor their
commitments and fully comply with the provisions of (U.N.)
Security Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general intends to send a mission to the region
in the coming days in response to the Security Council's statement
last week," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Greenstock, preident of the 15-member Security Council,
issued an oral statement last week, asking the U.N. chief to
consider ways to get the first-hand information on what is going
on in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On September 23, the Security Council adopted a resolution,
demanding an immediate cease-fire and the beginning of a
political dialogue on the Kosovo crisis, which broke out in
February this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his marathon talks with U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to
international ground and air verification of its compliance with
U.N. resolutions on Kosovo, Serbia's province of mainly ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
In his televised address to the nation, Milosevic said Tuesday
that his talks with Holbrooke had averted the threat of NATO air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements we have reached remove the danger of military
intervention against our country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement by Milosevid's office said his talks
with Holbrooke yielded a "constructive approach" for a political
solution that would give Kosovo autonomy within Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who make up some 90 percent of Kosovo's
province of 2 million, have been battling with Serbs for
independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
