<HEADLINE> Russia Denounces NATO Decision Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia described as a "mistake"
NATO's Monday decision on political consent to the use of force
against Yugoslavia with a 96-hour delay.
</P>
<P>
"Such steps are only complicating the political process of
settling the situation" in Kosovo, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Vladimir Rakhmanin told a briefing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman said Moscow welcomes "the progress
achieved at the latest talks in Belgrade on a political resolution
of the Kosovo problem, including the agreement between U.S.
special envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday morning, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov held
telephone conversations with his French, Italian and German
counterparts to consider "possible additional diplomatic efforts
to find solutions," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Itar-Tass, quoting sources with
the Russian Foreign Ministry, reported that the Contact Group,
which includes Russia, Britain, the United States, France and
Italy, will meet in Paris Thursday at the foreign ministers'
level.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin declined to comment on statements by some Russian
politicians that Russian arms may be supplied to Yugoslavia in the
event of NATO's military strikes.
</P>
<P>
"We do not intend to say which specific measures Russia may
take if NATO uses force against Yugoslavia, Rakhmanin said. "This
is a purposeful line of conduct."
</P>
<P>
Moscow "is not after a deterioration of its relations with
NATO," but if NATO implements any military operation against
Yugoslavia, its relations with Russia "will naturally require a
certain correction," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Russian State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, is sending a delegation to Belgrade shortly, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Duma Deputy Chairman Sergei Baburin, head of the anti-NATO
informal group in the Duma, said the delegation will leave for
Yugoslavia Thursday morning to help stave off the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
