<HEADLINE> Egypt Pledges More Mediation in Syria-Turkey Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Tuesday that Cairo will continue to mediate the
Turkish-Syrian dispute and hoped that the crisis will be resolved
through political means.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he has talked on telephone with his Turkish
counterpart Ismail Cem and that he will call up Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Sharaa later in the day to go on with efforts
to defuse tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I hope there is real progress towards defusing the
Turkish-Syrian row, and that we have succeeded in surmounting the
crisis," he told reporters, commenting on his talks with Turkish
and Syrian officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa paid a one-day visit to Ankara and Damascus Monday to
try to contain the crisis between the two neighbors. At the end of
the visit to Turkey, Moussa described his talks with Turkish
officials as "constructive and useful."
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Syria have always been
troublesome. Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring Turkish
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting
since 1984 for autonomy of the Kurdish minority in southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria, denying the charges, repeatedly voiced its concern and
fear over Turkey's close military alliance with Israel that
threatens Arab security.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has stepped up a war of words against Syria recently and
it war-like rhetoric has aroused fears of a regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi have shuttled between Turkey and Syria to try to
persuade the two neighbors to solve their disputes through
dialogs. 
