<HEADLINE> U.S. Says NATO to Protect Observers in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will station a stand-by military force near
Kosovo to protect unarmed observers of an agreement to end
violence in the Serbian province, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that what you will see is some kind of rapid
reaction capability which would be over the horizon, but not
located there in Kosovo," said Mike Doubleday, a Defense
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He told a Pentagon briefing that it was unlikely to include
American troops, but that final plans were not complete.
</P>
<P>
Doubleday also confirmed that U.S. and other NATO warplanes
would be available near Kosovo to protect unarmed NATO military
surveillance planes which will fly over the province to monitor
compliance with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said the surveillance planes could include high-flying
American U-2 spy planes, four-engine P-3 "Orion" and other
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed Monday to fully
comply with U.N. Security Council resolutions by withdrawing
forces from Kosovo and accepted an international inspection team
to monitor the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. President Bill Clinton warned that Milosevic must
keep its promises, otherwise NATO was ready to act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Iraq to Resume Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Monday once again called on Iraq to reverse its
decision and resume full cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council was briefed by Dr.
El-Baradei, the director-general of the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA), and by Richard Butler, the executive
chairman of the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM), on
their six-monthly reports on their activities in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On the IAEA report, the members of the council noted that the
report stated that should Iraq recommence full cooperation with
the IAEA, there would be no impediment to the full implementation
of the IAEA's plan for ongoing monitoring and verification, which
must be comprehensive and intrusive.
</P>
<P>
On the UNSCOM report, members of the council focused on the
need for Iraq to return to full cooperation if forward progress
was to be made.
</P>
<P>
On the chemical weapons and missiles files, members of the
council felt that there were not many items still to be resolved
if that cooperation was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
The council noted that on the biological weapons file, rather
more work was needed, which depended crucially on full disclosure
by Iraq, including information on biological weapons which they
already say they have.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the reports, the council once again called on
Iraq to take the decision to resume full cooperation with the IAEA
and the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced suspension of cooperation with the IAEA and the
UNSCOM in early August after the talks between Iraq and the UNSCOM
collapsed. The Security Council decided to suspend its regular
review of U.N. sanctions against Iraq until it resumes full
cooperation with the U.N. 
</P>
</TEXT>
