<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polio No Longer Threat to Mozambican Kids: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Polio has no longer posed a big
threat to the health of Mozambican children, a senior Mozambican
health official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Mozambican National Health Bureau Alexandre
Manguele said at a televised meeting that no polio cases have
been found in the last three to four years.
</P>
<P>
Manguele disclosed that during the second national polio
immunization campaign from September 28 to October 2, three
million children under the age of five years had been immunized
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government aimed at a 90-percent vaccination
rate among children under five during the first and second phases
of the anti-polio drive, said the health official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that epidemics monitoring networks have been set up
throughout the southern African country and every province has
its own well-trained medical personnels so that they can report
the diagnosed cases to higher institutions.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican First Lady Marcelina Chissano said at the meeting
that media have played an important role in the anti-polio
campaign because they can sensitize people on the harm of the
epidemic through illustrative images. 
</P>
</TEXT>
