<HEADLINE> Mandela Upbeat About Lesotho Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Tuesday reiterated his optimism that a solution
would be reached in Lesotho to end the political crisis in the
tiny mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said this after meeting with Lesotho Queen's mother
Mamqhato Seeiso and Prince Seeiso in South Africa's eastern port
city of Durban.
</P>
<P>
The South African president discussed with the Lesotho royal
members about the situation in the kingdom, which has been
unrestful since August following allegations by opposition
parties of May 23 election fraud.
</P>
<P>
Mandela told reporters that he had invited the queen to brief
him on the Lesotho situation and to get her views in order to
find a solution to the country's crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that we are on the right track to settle
Lesotho's problems, and I believe the political leaders and all
other people involved will come to an understanding to resolve
the problem," South African Press Association quoted Mandela as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he did not want the media to pose any questions
to the queen and the prince as the Lesotho matter was sensitive
and question could endanger the progress that had been made.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the president said that he believed a breakthrough
in Lesotho's political problem was imminent and that a Southern
African Development Community (SADC) proposal for a political
solution to the kingdom's problem would win in the end.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, a land-locked country surrounded by South Africa, has
been in turmoil since its May election, which opposition parties
claim were rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD).
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Botswana sent their troops to Lesotho in the
name of the SADC to help the Lesotho government to restore law
and security in late September.
</P>
<P>
The LCD and opposition party alliance are due to hold their
third round of peace talks over political disputes. South
African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi, head of the
SADC delegation, will chair the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
