<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Start in Arusha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The third round of
Burundi peace talks opened Tuesday in north Tanzania's Arusha
town with conflicting parties having a general debate of
democracy in the central Africa country.
</P>
<P>
Mark Bomani, a senior aide to the talks mediator Julius
Nyerere, former president of Tanzania, told Xinhua over telephone
that the debate will continue Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, aimed at ending the five-year civil war in
Burundi, have brought together the Burundian government
delegation, the National Assembly, and various warring factions
like FRODEBU, a pro-Hutu party, pro-Tutsi UPRONA, and the largest
rebel group CNDD.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian government delegation is led by Minister of
Peace Process Ambroise Niyonsaba.
</P>
<P>
According to other sources at the meeting, the items on the
talks agenda include debate of good governance and democracy,
choosing chairmen of five committees to discuss aspects of the
Burundi conflict, start of work of the committees, discussions on
peace and security in Burundi, among others.
</P>
<P>
"The chairmen of the five commissions will be appointed
tomorrow," Bomani said, adding that consultations were conducted
Tuesday on the candidates for the chairmen. However, he declined
to name them.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks had been planned to open Monday but
was postponed to Tuesday to wait for the arrival of more
delegates.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which may last more than 10 days, are attended by
observers from the United Nations, the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the OAU, have
imposed economic sanctions on Burundi since August 1996 shortly
after Major Pierre Buyoya toppled a civilian government led by
President Ntibantunganya.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed
in Burundi since October 1993, in a series of massacres and in
armed conflict between Burundi's Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Warring parties signed a cease-fire agreement in the first
round of talks in June and dwelt mainly on the genesis of the
Burundi conflict at the second round of talks in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
