<HEADLINE> Iraqi Leaders Discuss Issues Surrounding UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi leaders made no decision
on whether to resume cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors at
their meeting Tuesday, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam Hussein chaired the joint meeting of the
Revolutionary Command Council and the regional command of the
Baath party.
</P>
<P>
INA said the meeting discussed the results of Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz's recent New York talks with the U.N. chief
and member states of the Security Council, but reached no decision.
</P>
<P>
It said the Iraqi leadership would continue with the discussion
of this issue in the following days.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided on August 5 to suspend cooperation with the United
Nations Special Committee (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic
Energy Agency, complaining that UNSCOM is dominated by the
U.S. and bent on prolonging sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council responded on September 9 by canceling its
regular reviews of crippling sanctions. But in the meantime, the
council promised it would conduct a comprehensive review of the
sanctions regime once Iraq resumes cooperation with its weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq criticized the council's response and said it would not
rescind its ban on U.N. weapons inspections until UNSCOM was
restructured to curb U.S. influence and that the sanctions are
lifted or eased.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock between Iraq and the Security Council,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan invited Aziz to New York at the
end of September to discuss Iraq's relations with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Aziz spent most of his time in New York evaluating the offered
review by the council and holding three meetings with Annan, but
he said he needed to report to the leadership, which can decide if
the cooperation can be resumed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM verifies that it is free
of chemical, biological weapons and long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
INA said Tuesday's meeting also discussed U.S. interferences in
Iraq's internal affairs. U.S. Congress invited Iraq's Kurdish
leaders to Washington for a conciliatory meeting and provided them
with money and weapons.
</P>
<P>
The meeting said U.S. "wanton interferences in Iraq's internal
affairs" contradict the principles of international laws and the
spirit and text of the Security Council resolutions which call for
respect of Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
It also accused UNSCOM of spying on Iraq in coordination with
the U.S. administration, and revealing confidential and sensitive
information about Iraq's security and armed forces to Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
