<HEADLINE> Regional Environmental Conference Open in Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Committee of the
Sixth General Assembly of the Asia-Pacific Parliamentarians
Conference on Environment and Development (APPCED), which will run
through October 18, ended its first meeting today with a decision
that the next general assembly will be held in December 1999 in
Chiangmai Province, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The next assembly will focus on discussions related to
preventing urban pollution, especially the waste treatment,
according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
Lu Congmin, deputy leader of the Chinese delegation to the
APPCED and deputy secretary general of the National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, will serve as president of
the Drafting Committee for the "Guilin Declaration".
</P>
<P>
The committee plans to maintain close contacts with
international and regional organizations such as the World Health
Organization (WHO) and APEC, and will invite said organizations
to attend the next assembly.
</P>
<P>
The committee suggested that developed countries attend the
conference to discuss global environmental protection, especially
problems related to atmospheric changes adversely affecting
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Peter Hodgson, acting president of the APPCED Executive
Committee and member of New Zealand House of Representatives,
praised the Chinese NPC Standing Committee and the Guilin city
government for their excellent preparations for the conference. He
also welcomed the participation of representatives from more
organizations from around the world.
</P>
<P>
Qu Geping, leader of the Chinese delegation and member of the
of the Chinese NPC Standing Committee, expressed China's hope for
a highly successful conference.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 representatives from 29 countries and
international organizations are attending the Guilin assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
