<HEADLINE> Myanmar Frees More NLD Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities have
allowed 24 members of the National League for Democracy (NLD) to
go home since September 14 after "view exchanges" with them,
according to a government statement issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will let more NLD members go home if the NLD
leadership cooperates, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the NLD Tuesday, a total of
979 of its party members including 203 parliament
representatives-elect and 776 party organizers have been detained
by the authorities since May 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The NLD has denied that the authorities had exchanged views
with its detained members, saying that they were, in fact,
"interrogated."
</P>
<P>
On September 16, the NLD formed a 10-member committee
representing the parliament elected in the 1990 multi-party
general election and set up a People's Parliament after its
deadline for the parliament to be convened was ignored by the
government.
</P>
<P>
After the NLD's formation of the People's Parliament, the
government has organized a series of mass rallies in different
states and divisions, denouncing the NLD's move.
</P>
<P>
The NLD said in a letter to the chairman of the State Peace and
Development Council on Tuesday that the authorities are
"illegally" using people from all walks of life who are under
"pressure" for the expression of "the people's desire," creating
further political confusion.
</P>
<P>
The NLD stressed that it reserves the right to organize similar
mass rallies to present facts on the current situation in Myanmar
as it is a legal political party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
