<HEADLINE> Communique of the Third Plenum of the 15th Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Third Plenary Session of
the 15th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
was held in Beijing on October 12-14, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The session was atteqded by 185 members and 148 alternate
members, of the CPC Central Committee. Members of the Standing
Committee of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection and
leading members of relevant departments attended the session as
nonvoting delegates.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central Committee,
made an important speech at the session which was presided over by
the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
It was held at the session that agriculture, rural work and
farmers are important issues that have a vital bearing on China's
reforms, opening up and modernization drive. To fulfill the grand
trans-century development goals set forth at the 15th National
Congress of the CPC, efforts must be made to further strengthen
agriculture as the foundation of the national economy, maintain
sustained agricultural and rural economic development, ensure the
steady increase of the income of farmers and maintain stability in
rural areas. China's reform first started from rural areas. And
at the time of the 20th anniversary of China's reform and opening
up, and in the face of the impact of the Asian financial crisis
and the challenges arising from economic globalization, it is
timely and necessary for the session to concentrate on studying
agriculture and the rural issues. The session examined and
approved the "Resolution of the CPC Central Committee on Several
Major Issues Concerning Agriculture and Rural Work".
</P>
<P>
Those who attended the session spoke highly of the monumental
achievements and vast experience gained in rural reform over the
past two decades. They were of the unanimous view that the
household contract system with remuneration linked to output,
abolition of the people's commune, the breakthrough in the planned
economy mould and the development of the socialist market economy
have greatly kindled the enthusiasm of hundreds of millions of
Chinese farmers, and emancipated and developed productive forces,
thus bringing the historic, tremendous changes to rural economy
and social development. These great changes have led and promoted
the all-round reforms of the country and have further explored a
road of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, which
suits China's actual situation, and have thus made important
contributions to the sustained and fast growth of the national
economy and to maintaining social stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Ruling Party Rejects SADC Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's ruling party
Wednesday rejected a Southern African Development Community
(SADC) proposal to set up a transitional council for fresh
elections.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) said it did not agree
with the proposal because it would be tantamount to overthrowing
the country's constitution, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the SADC proposal, the transitional structure will have
access to information held by the government that is relevant to
the elections. It will also take decisions on all electoral
matters including the role of the police, the military, the
intelligence, finance, foreign affairs, and media and
publications.
</P>
<P>
The powerful structure will review Lesotho's electoral system
and appoint a new Independent Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
In a document given to multi-party talks Wednesday, the
governing LCD said: "If the government connives at the
jettisoning of the constitution without assessing the will of the
people, it will be committing fraud on the people of Lesotho and
the electorate, and such act will be considered by history as an
unforgivable transgression."
</P>
<P>
SAPA said it got access to the document.
</P>
<P>
In the document, the LCD said a transitional structure was
irrelevant as the country was not in transition.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has an elected parliament and government, and an
agreement on fresh elections that will result in a new elected
parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
The LCD said it had no problem with the part of the SADC
proposal outlining the objectives sought to be achieved by the
transitional structure. But it said no such structure could be
established under the present constitution without grossly
undermining the fundamental pillars of the country's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
"If the structure is intended to facilitate the conduct of
free and fair elections, it should be described truthfully as a
structure to facilitate the holding of free and fair elections in
relation to the existing electoral law," the LCD said in a
nine-page response to the SADC proposal.
</P>
<P>
The document said the LCD would argue that nowhere in the
world were political parties empowered to conduct general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Sets Free More NLD Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities have
allowed 24 members of the National League for Democracy (NLD) to
go home since September 14 after "view exchanges" with them,
according to a government statement issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will let more NLD members go home if the NLD
leadership cooperates, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the NLD Tuesday, a total of
979 of its party members including 203 parliament
representatives-elect and 776 party organizers have been detained
by the authorities since May 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The NLD has denied that the authorities had exchanged views
with its detained members, saying that they were, in fact,
"interrogated."
</P>
<P>
On September 16, the NLD formed a 10-member committee
representing the parliament elected in the 1990 multi-party
general election and set up a People's Parliament after its
deadline for the parliament to be convened was ignored by the
government.
</P>
<P>
After the NLD's formation of the People's Parliament, the
government has organized a series of mass rallies in different
states and divisions, denouncing the NLD's move.
</P>
<P>
The NLD said in a letter to the chairman of the State Peace and
Development Council on Tuesday that the authorities are
"illegally" using people from all walks of life who are under
"pressure" for the expression of "the people's desire," creating
further political confusion.
</P>
<P>
The NLD stressed that it reserves the right to organize similar
mass rallies to present facts on the current situation in Myanmar
as it is a legal political party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
