<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed nearly one percent weaker Wednesday after the Japanese
market shed early gains and slipped into negative territory.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 22.9 points to
2465.6, just off the day's lows.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the Nikkei index lost 172 points to 13071. The Hang
Seng, in Hong Kong, lost 168.82 points to close at 8,840.01.
</P>
<P>
"There is no great surprise, our market was a little bit worse
than expected with the Nikkei lower, Hong Kong drifting lower in
the day and no significant leads overnight," Shaw Stockbroking
broker Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
"Gold was also weaker with brokers a bit disappointed in not
breaking through the 300-U.S.-dollar (an ounce) level this week."
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index fell 43.7 points to 4281.2
while the all resources index dropped 5.4 points to 1011.1.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 23.1 points, nearly two percent, down at
1152 with the gold bullion price in Sydney closing at 296.45 U.S.
dollars an ounce, compared to 296.75 previously.
</P>
<P>
In the diversified mining stocks, BHP added five cents, Rio
Tinto climbed 12 cents while WMC dipped 13 cents and MIM lost two
cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking index was 43.1 points adrift at 5171.9 with
National Australia Bank adding 2.2 cents, while Commonwealth
slipped 15 cents, Westpac dropped 7.6 cents and ANZ shed 22.3
cents.
</P>
<P>
Installment receipts in Telstra were three cents cheaper, it
was the highest turnover security with 15.826 million receipts
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
News Corp descended seven cents while its preferred stock was
8.5 cents weaker after Tuesday's annual general meeting in
Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 409.04 million shares worth 1.101 billion
Australian dollars (693.63 million U.S. dollars) with 401 rises,
626 falls and 371 steady trades. 
</P>
