<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Promises New Style in Second Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia's re-elected Prime
Minister John Howard promised a new style of government in his
second term Wednesday and warned coalition MPs that the next
election could not be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
Howard said at the first meeting of Liberal Party MPs and
senators since the October 3 election that the election victory
was more profound than his victory over Paul Keating in 1996, and
the victory exploded many Australian political myths and proved a
government could go to the people with a comprehensive program of
reform.
</P>
<P>
Howard and Treasurer Peter Costello were unanimously re-elected
party parliamentary leader and deputy at the meeting, while Robert
Hill and Richard Alston were appointed Senate leader and deputy
leader respectively.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he would now turn his mind to
appointing the new cabinet, which is likely to be announced over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would end up with a majority of between
10 and 14 seats in the new parliament, which will meet for the
first time on November 10.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the coalition would have to work hard to win the
next election, which would be fought on different issues and in a
different political environment.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he promised a new-look government which would
put aboriginal reconciliation and social issues high on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be a different prime minister in many ways than I was
last time," he said. "I'll have different goals. I will have come
through a different experience, and I will have different things I
want to achieve."
</P>
<P>
Howard said Australia is now ready for the referendum on the
republic, and whatever the outcome is, Australia would not be
damaged by the process.
</P>
<P>
Despite the upbeat nature of the meeting, Howard warned that
One Nation Party remains a problem for the coalition. "We should
not assume that the threat posed by One Nation, particularly to
the coalition side of politics, has gone."
</P>
<P>
"The One Nation party took about eight or nine percent from us
and delivered half or a bit more of that to the Labor Party via
its preferences. And that of course carries a message for us."
</P>
<P>
He said the coalition has much work to do to encourage One
Nation voters back to the fold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
