<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Optimistic Over Meeting With Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu expressed optimism Wednesday over the upcoming
Israeli-Palestinian summit, saying it could break the deadlock in
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, Netanyahu
told reporters that the Israeli government and people hope for the
success of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is scheduled to meet with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and the United States President Bill Clinton on Thursday in
Washington in a bid to reach an agreement on Israeli further
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli leader urged the Palestinians to live up to the
commitments to clamp down on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
A longstanding U.S. proposal calls for Israeli withdrawal from
additional 13 percent of the West Bank in return for Palestinian
crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the plan, but the Israelis have
proposed a modification demanding that 3 percent of the land be
turned into a nature reserve where the Palestinians have limited
powers.
</P>
<P>
Hassan expressed cautious optimism about the outcome of the
summit, saying that he hoped the meeting will constitute an
important step towards a breakthrough in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, is
keen on helping advance the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu arrived here early in the day and returned home after
the talks. This is Netanyahu's first visit to Jordan since
bilateral relations soured in September 1997 due to an
assassination attempt by Israeli secret agents against a Hamas
(Islamic Resistance Movement) leader in Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
