<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup History Against Primorac By Sporstwriter Cao Jianjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 14 (Xinhua) -- History is not on Zoran
Primorac's side.
</P>
<P>
The world third-ranked Croatian, who won the 1993 and 1997
table tennis World Cup, faces a mission impossible to defend his
crown although he was drawn into an easy group on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
None of the former World Cup winners has successfully defended
his title since the annual event was inaugurated in 1980.
Primorac is no exception, admitted his coach Novakovic Zladtko.
</P>
<P>
Primorac, Qater Open winner and European championships
runner-up this year, was drawn into Group C with South Korean Kim
Taek Soo, Peter Karlsson of Sweden and world No. 59 Liu Song of
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
European champion and world No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus
was bundled in Group A with reigning world champion Jan-Ove
Waldner of Sweden, Kalinikos Kreanga of Greece and Oceania
champion Mark Smythe of Australia.
</P>
<P>
World No. 2 Kong Linghui and rising star Ma Lin, both from
China, were drawn into Group B. The other players in this group
are 1994 World Cup champion Jean-Philippe Gatien of France and
African champion Ali Sareh from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
China's Olympic champion Liu Guoliang was pitted against
Jean-Michel Saive of Belgium, Jorg Rosskopf of Germany and Johnny
Huang of Canada in Group D, which the Croatian coach called
"Group of Death".
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to say who are going to snatch two quarter-final
berths in this group," said Zlatko. "Liu has better chance, but I
can't predict the other survivor."
</P>
<P>
The group competition will kick off on Thursday, with top two
players of each group securing quarter-final spots.
</P>
<P>
Zlatko said Primorac was set to make last eight but he didn't
know how far his student would go since.
</P>
<P>
"In the semifinals, Primorac may take on Kong Linghui or Liu
Guoliang and his survival chance is slim," said Zlatko.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua tipped Kong as China's only
title hopeful.
</P>
<P>
"Kong is consistent and in form and he is our best chance,"
said Cai.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guoliang is being plagued by shoulder injury while Ma Lin
lacks experience, added Cai.
</P>
<P>
China has won the World Cup for 10 times, with Guo Yuehua and
Ma Wenge each winning twice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Mountain to  Climb  (by Tan Xinmu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- When Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat begin
Thursday the Washington summit aimed at clinching a deal on the
second Israeli redeployment, they will surely have a big mountain
to conquer.
</P>
<P>
Gaps between the two sides have been narrowed after almost
three months of direct talks and rounds of U.S. mediation, but
differences still remain.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinians are only demanding that Israel pullback
its troops from another 13 percent of the West Bank as a
U.S. initiative calls for, the Israelis will give them a long list
of tasks they have to work on.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his departure, Netanyahu has laid out nine
points detailing the specific issues the Palestinians have to
resolve, including fighting terrorism, reducing the Palestinian
force, confiscating illegally-held weapons and annulling those
articles in the Palestinian Covenant calling for destruction of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
On top of the list, meanwhile the harshest, is the demand that
"nothing is settled until everything is settled." To be more
specific, Israel will sign an accord only when the two sides
agree on the whole package.
</P>
<P>
This means that the Palestinians will face a choice in the
negotiations: getting part of the West Bank and making
concessions on many other issues, or getting no land.
</P>
<P>
Even if Netanyahu is determined to climb the mountain to get a
deal, his legs have been, to some extent, shackled by his partners
in his coalition.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying him to the U.S. will be Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon, defender of the interests of the Jewish settlers. Sharon
will take part in the negotiations, but he has already reiterated
that he is against a 13 percent withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Although Netanyahu's cabinet ministers have given him the
mandate to negotiate, they have linked an agreement to
Palestinian security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
While Jewish settlers have been protesting daily over the past
few days and are planning a massive demonstration later Wednesday
to warn Netanyahu against striking a deal with the Palestinians,
the right-wingers in his government have reiterated their threats
to topple the government. Some of the right-wingers have begun to
turn their words into actions.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party (NRP), the extreme rightist
coalition party, demanded at a cabinet meeting Tuesday that
Netanyahu not hand over any land to the Palestinians unless they
extradite suspects in attacks on Israelis and revise the
Palestinian Covenant.
</P>
<P>
If the prime minister wraps up a deal without meeting these
conditions, the NRP will bring down the government, party
officials warned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Land of Israel Front, a group of rightist
legislators crossing party lines, is actively seeking a candidate
to run for prime minister in the next general election.
</P>
<P>
The group announced Tuesday that from the moment the
government decides on withdrawal, it will "move to the
opposition, and will vote no confidence in the government on all
subjects." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Admit Foreign Exchange Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 110 enterprises in south
China's Guangdong province today voluntarily confessed to
fraudulent practices in purchasing foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) issued
an announcement on October 7 that enterprises guilty of fraudulent
transactions involving less than five million U.S. dollars would
received lenient treatment if they confessed their offences within
48 hours.
</P>
<P>
SAFE's Guangdong Branch issued the announcement via the local
media on October 8.
</P>
<P>
A total of 93 Guangdong enterprises entered voluntarily
confessions by October 11, according to SAFE.  
</P>
