<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEF Delegation Arrives in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A delegation from the Taiwan
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), led by Chairman Koo Chen-fu,
arrived in Shanghai this afternoon for a landmark visit to the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS), welcomed the
delegation on its arrival at Shanghai's Hongqiao International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
Koo, chairman of Taiwan's highest authorized nongovernmental
organization, is leading a 12-member delegation on the first
mainland visits of its kind. The delegation will visit both
Shanghai and Beijing over the next six days.
</P>
<P>
ARATS and SEF reached a September agreement calling for ARATS
President Wang Daohan and Koo to meet several times to engage in
free exchanges of views on prevailing issues.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Wang and Koo held their first meeting in
Singapore in April 1993 signified a historical progress in the
development of cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference shortly after his arrival, Koo
told reporters that he was filled with overwhelming excitement
when once again arriving on the soil of the Chinese mainland after
some 53 years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he expressed the hope that his meeting with Wang will
enhance relations between ARATS and SEF, and in turn greatly help
improve cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Koo is scheduled to leave for Beijing on Friday. President
Jiang Zemin, Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, and Chen Yunlin, director
of the State Council's Taiwan Affairs Office, will meet with Koo
in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan delegation is expected to visit the Pudong New Area,
the Shanghai Stock Exchange, the metropolitan's Television Tower,
the Shanghai Museum, Yuyuan Garden and the Chenghuang Temple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sound Growth, Grim Future for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The 48 U.N.-designated poorest
countries in the world recorded solid performance last year with
a growth rate exceeding that of the world economy as a whole,
said a U.N. report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, they still have to expect a grim future as their
shares in the world economy continue downwards and the risk of
further marginalization remains high, said a report by the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product (GDP) in these least developed
countries (LDCs) averaged 4.8 percent in 1997, compared with 3.2
percent for the world economy, according to the most comprehensive
report on the world's weakest economies, the 14th one in its series.
</P>
<P>
The LDCs saw GDP increases of 5.5 percent and 4.5 percent in
1996 and 1995 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Despite the modest decline in the growth figure compared with
that in 1996, per capita rise last year benefited two-thirds of
these poorest countries in the world community, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
"Over half of the group -- 25 countries -- have now recorded
real increases in growth for three or more consecutive years,"
the report claimed.
</P>
<P>
In those LDCs which have enjoyed a relatively fast growth for
years, growth now depends less on agricultural expansion than on
the output in industrial sector (in Lesotho and Uganda) or in
services (in Ethiopia and Mozambique), it said.
</P>
<P>
However, poor weather conditions and the Asian financial
crisis took their toll in Africa, and declining commodity prices
on the world market especially undermined African growth, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Lack of export diversification further weakened their
economies following sharp fluctuations in the prices of their
exports intricated by the Asian monetary crisis and their
continued vulnerability to external shocks.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past decade, most LDCs' exports have been limited to
two or three products, almost all of which are sold in raw or
semi-processed form," the report lamented.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, their shares in the world economy continued to
decline. The LDCs' output in 1996 represented less than one
percent of the World's GDP while their export share in 1995 (the
latest figure) was only 0.4 percent, down from 0.5 percent
between 1985-1990.
</P>
<P>
As a group, LDCs received only 1.5 percent of foreign direct
investment (FDI) flowing to developing countries last year. And,
as a percentage of total inflows worldwide, their share was a
minute 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The debt picture in these 48 countries also remain "very
grim." Their combined external debt stood at 134 billion U.S.
Dollars in 1996 (the latest figure) -- a full 90 percent debt of
their combined GDP, down slightly from 136 billion Dollars in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The 48 LDCs, of which 33 are from Africa, have a total
pupolation of over 600 million and an average per capita GDP of
about 230 U.S. Dollars each, according to the lastest U.N. data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
