<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Open to Settlement of Marcos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
remains open and prepared to hold informal talks on the settlement
of former president Ferdinand Marcos' ill-gotten wealth, an
official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora made the remarks in response
to recent statements by a member of the Marcoses that they are
backing out of the negotiations with the government.
</P>
<P>
The best solution to the disposing of the Marcos wealth will be
for the family of the late president to settle with the
government, Zamora said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the government can not push the
settlement, "unless everybody is willing to sit down around the
table."
</P>
<P>
"It is possible they (the Marcoses) have changed their minds.
We recognize that everybody has the right to change his or her
mind," Zamora said, stressing that entering into a settlement with
the government is a matter for the Marcos family to decide.
</P>
<P>
Zamora remains hopeful that the Marcos family will still decide
to settle with the government, saying "they may be in the first
flash of, you know, triumph because of the acquittal of Mrs.
Marcos."
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court earlier acquitted former first lady Imelda
Marcos of the graft charges filed against her, saving her from a
maximum jail term of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Marcos was accused of amassing at least 5 billion dollars
during his 20 years' rule of the country.
</P>
<P>
The government, the Marcoses and human rights victims during
the Marcos regime are trying to sit down together to settle the
570 million dollars of Marcos wealth the government recovered from
Swiss banks early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
