<HEADLINE> Israeli Politicians Wish Washington Summit Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli politicians expressed
their hope Wednesday that the upcoming Washington summit on
Mideast peace process be successful.
</P>
<P>
The Washington summit between U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat will begin at the White House Thursday and then the
three-day summit will be moved to Wye Plantation in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The main topic for the summit is to reach an agreement on
Israel's further troop redeployment in the West Bank and on other
issues concerning the peace process.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman, through the Israel Radio, expressed
his best wishes to Netanyahu and his delegation, saying the peace
process must be moved forward.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak, Israeli opposition Labor Party chairman said that
his party will support the agreement on redeployment if it is
reached.
</P>
<P>
The Labor will support the government on this issue, but that
does not mean the Labor will support the government on
everything, Barak told the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Israeli former prime minister Shimon Peres said he believes
the Washington summit will produce positive results and the
agreement on redeployment could be signed.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon told the Israel
Radio that preparations for the Washington summit will continue
right up to the last moment in the U.S. and it is possible for the
summit to reach a redeployment agreement.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli delegation should be strong enough to insist
on the Palestinian side to fulfill their commitment in the peace
process, he added.
</P>
<P>
In prepartion for the summit, Netanyahu presided over a long
cabinet meeting on Tuesday and formulated a nine-point principle
for guiding the peace talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Sharon went to Amman Wednesday morning for
pre-summit consultations with Crown Prince Hassan. 
</P>
