<HEADLINE> Vietnamese PM Calls for Fight Against Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai gave order to step up fight against smuggling, Vietnam
News Agency (VNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Khai, the report said, has instructed Vietnam's leading
officials of relevant ministries and chairmen of the people's
committees of provinces and cities to continue waging the
nationwide fight against smuggling and trade fraud.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese prime minister said that thanks to synchronous
measures taken since early this year, the fight against smuggling
and trade fraud has obtained initial positive results. In the
first nine months of this year, these measures helped restore
order in trade activities, increase budget revenue from taxes, and
promote domestic production.
</P>
<P>
Khai asked relevant ministries, branches and localities to push
up the  fight against smuggling and trade fraud while trying to
maintain trade activities and market prices, particularly prices
of taxed import goods.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Ministry of Public Security to make greater
efforts to detect organized cases of smuggling, contraband goods
trafficking and fraud trade.
</P>
<P>
He added that drastic measures must be taken to fight smuggling
along railway lines, and goods confiscated must be quickly settled
to provide financial support to those fighting smuggling at the
commune and district levels.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,850 cases of smuggling, contraband goods trafficking and
trade fraud were detected by the customs throughout the country
in July and August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
