<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Delegation Leaves for Belgrade on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Russian
State Duma, or the lower house of parliament, left here for
Belgrade Wednesday for consultations over the Kosovo issue,
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which is led by Duma Vice Chairman Sergei
Baburin, aimed "to promote a peaceful settlement and rule out
any use of force" in Kosovo, said Vladimir Zorin, a member of the
delegation and Chairman of the Duma Committee for Nationalities,
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
In Yugoslavia, the delegation is expected to hold talks with
leaders in Belgrade as well as in Kosovo, Zorin said.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the Kosovo crisis with the Chechen conflicts, Zorin
said that "Russia has its own bitter experience which shows that
the use of force in tackling ethnic and territorial problems ends
in deadlock."
</P>
<P>
In the case of Kosovo, Yugoslavia's territorial integrity must
be preserved, and at the same time, the problems of the Kosovo
Albanians must also be solved, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Arbatov, vice chairman of the Duma Defense Committee and
member of the delegation, said that the Russian deputies' tasks
are to prevent a "unilateral solution of the problem. Peace in the
Balkans means not only calming down the Serbs, but also curbing
the separatists' terrorist activity."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov will fly to
Paris Wednesday evening to attend a session of the Contact Group
foreign ministers, where U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke
would report to them the results of his talks in Belgrade,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov has expressed his optimism on the issue Tuesday evening
in an interview with the National TV.
</P>
<P>
Although the situation in Kosovo remains complicated, signs of
advancement toward agreements which may lead to political
settlement of the conflict have appeared, he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo appeared to be slightly heartening
since Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic reached
agreements on the current crisis Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
