<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Stopping Certain Car Levies (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China will have 8-percent
growth this year despite the Asian financial crisis and certain
levies by governmental offices have become a problem.
</P>
<P>
The State Council is telling all governments to stop the
illicit levies on enterprises and individuals and their first
targets are levies on roads and automotives.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Ministry, there are more than 2,000
kinds of levies at various levels of government, worth 400 billion
yuan (48 billion U.S. dollars) annually, accounting for half the
Chinese government's revenues.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Machine-Building Industry Bureau, the
amount of governmental fees that an individual pays for a new car
is equal to nearly half the sticker price. If the individual wants
to operate the car as a taxi, the fees are greater than the value
of the car.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhensheng, an official of the State Machine-Building
Industry Bureau, said that all localities want to draw
profits from the promising car market by introducing excessive
levies on it. He said that excessive levies restricted the car
market by making costs of running a car unbearable for consumers.
</P>
<P>
China's output of automotives dropped markedly in the third
quarter from that of the previous quarter due to decreased market
demands. According forecast by the State Information Center,
China's total demands for automotives will be 50,000 units less
than beginning-of-year prediction.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of pricing says that the root of the
problem is the interest that government offices have in these
levies and that they always have access to a large part of the
levy revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Stopping Certain Cars Levies (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng points out that excessive
levies have not only severely eroded the national tax base and
indirectly reduced revenues, but have created favorable conditions
for corruption.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has instructed the State Development Planning
Commission, the Ministry of Finance and other government
departments to draw up plans to cancel these road and automobile
levies.
</P>
<P>
From the beginning of the new year, most automobile levies will
be eliminated, with only a small number remaining. A large number
will be replaced by taxes and commercial charges similar to taxes.
</P>
<P>
Automobile industry sources say that the industry has long
called for the removal of so-called road maintenance, road and
bridge tolls, passenger transport fees, and purchase levies. The
industry hopes that the government will replace these levies with
fuel taxes and sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
This year, authorities have abolished 29 types of
administrative levies and 147 fund raising programs, which is
expected to reduce the finance burden of enterprises by 13 billion
yuan per year. In the past 12 months, governments at all levels
have cancelled 20,700 types of levies on enterprises, worth 49.3
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Finance, the amount of taxes and
fees that Chinese enterprises paid accounted for 25 to 30 percent
of the GDP, which is higher than for other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
A China Automotive Industry Development Research Center analyst
says that stopping the levies will help infrastructure
construction and promote economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Remove Obstacles to Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
acting swiftly to remove legal obstacles to the imposition of
death penalty which was considered a powerful deterrent to
criminality.
</P>
<P>
Justice Secretary Serafin Cuevas said here Wednesday that his
department will present to the Supreme Court this week amendments
implementing rules on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court upheld on Tuesday the Constitutionality of
lethal injection as the mode of execution in implementing the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
However, the court ordered the Department of Justice to correct
two sections of enabling law for lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
One section suspends the death sentence for pregnant women by
up to three years while the other section requires that the manual
for implementation of the death sentence be kept confidential. The
two sections are inconsistent with other laws.
</P>
<P>
"We have studied the necessary amendments, and will present
them before the high court Wednesday or Thursday," Cuevas said.
</P>
<P>
At least 700 convicts have been sentenced to death for various
heinous crimes since the country resumed the penalty in 1994. But
due to disputes over how to implement the penalty, none of the
criminals has been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supertyphoon Lashes Northern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Supertyphoon "Iliang" spared
Metro Manila but battered several provinces in Luzon, the northern
Philippines, an initial report by the National Disaster
Coordinating Council said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Iliang, with powerful center winds at 265
kilometers per hour, unloaded its fury in Northern Luzon and the
Bicol region.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon signal was raised over Metro Manila but the howler
changed course, sparing it from imminent devastation.
</P>
<P>
Metro Manila only experienced rains the whole day Wednesday.
The rain is expected to last a day or two as Iliang exits from the
country Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The report said 10 electrical posts were uprooted in Isabela,
one of the hardest-hit provinces, while 74 families were forced to
evacuate from their homes in Calabanga, Camarines Sur province due
to rising flood waters.
</P>
<P>
With such a fury, Iliang, the strongest typhoon to hit the
country this year, could bring devastation in its path, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado, who also chairs the
National Disaster Coordinating Council, ordered all provincial
units to prepare for all contingencies, including evacuation of
people and storing food and medicine supplies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council is closely monitoring lahar flows from
Mount Pinatubo which erupted on June 12, 1991 after being dormant
for 600 years. About 500 people were killed in the most
spectacular volcanic eruption recorded during the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
No lahar flow has been sighted so far but the rains brought
about by supertyphoon Iliang could trigger a massive lahar flow in
Pampanga, Tarlac and Zambales, particularly in areas near the
dreaded volcano, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
