<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Moves to Curb Incursion of Chadian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's army is conducting a
joint operation in northeastern border areas in conjunction with
Chad and Niger to arrest the incursion of Chadian rebels into
Nigeria, the Defense Headquarters confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of Defense Information Lt. Col. Sam Tella was
quoted as saying Tuesday that the move code-named "Operation
Flush Out" is primarily aimed at flushing out Chadian rebels who
have turned bandits and occupying several villages in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said the Nigerian Air Force and the land-based forces of
the Army are leading the operation with the Police, Customs,
Immigration and other security agencies involved, The Guardian
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Chief of Defense Staff Air Vice Marshal Al-Amin
Daggash and the General Officer commanding 3 Armored Divisions
visited the area of operation during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Defense spokesman also confirmed that Defense Headquarters
has written to all states of west Africa to beef up security to
arrest any of the rebels who might flee the operational area to
the hinterland.
</P>
<P>
The Chadian rebels are concentrated in the Maduguri area,
northeastern Nigeria, Tella said, adding that "we've cordoned off
the area. We're still in operation."
</P>
<P>
According to him, last week, about 21 persons were killed in a
dawn armed robbery operation by the Chadian rebels who were
believed to invade the country through Bauchi State.
</P>
<P>
In the robbery operation, about 51 vehicles were ransacked and
their occupants forcefully dispossessed of their money and other
belongings.
</P>
<P>
Tella said that "Operation Flush Out" which started on October
1 is being conducted around Lake Chad where the rebels are
believed to have their bases.
</P>
<P>
The operation is embarked upon "in response to appeals for
security of lives and the territorial security of Chad and Niger
who are our immediate neighbors," he noted.
</P>
<P>
For the past several years, Chadian rebels have been engaged
in banditry, armed robbery and generally making life difficult
for Nigerians in many northern states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
