<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Ready to Help With Lesotho Election: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan said Wednesday that his organization was ready
to help Lesotho make the upcoming general election a success,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read at multi-party talks in Maseru, Annan
said: "The U.N. stands ready to provide any assistance that will
make the (electoral) process a success."
</P>
<P>
He urged rival political parties in Lesotho to work hard to
resolve outstanding issues so that a climate conducive to free
and fair elections could be created.
</P>
<P>
The talks, chaired by South African Safety and Security
Minister Sydney Mufamadi, began at 10.30 a.m. (0830 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Southern African Development Community (SADC) spokesman Ronnie
Mamoepa earlier said delegates of the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD) and opposition parties would discuss how to make
sure all parties had an equal chance in Lesotho's elections, to
be held in 15 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The parties have said there would be robust debate around the
issue of a government of national unity before the election.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's general election was held on May 23 this year. But
opposition parties rejected the results, claiming the election
was rigged in favor of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Protests by opposition supporters since early August pushed
the country into anarchy and finally led to military intervention
by South African and Botswanan troops, under the auspices of the
SADC.
</P>
<P>
The LCD and its opposition rivals agreed on October 2 to hold
fresh elections in 15 to 18 months, but are still wrangling over
who should run the country until that time.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties insist that a government of national unity
should be established, but the idea was rejected by the LCD.
</P>
<P>
During the second round of multi-party talks on October 5, the
SADC proposed a transitional structure alongside the LCD
government. However, it is still not clear whether the rival
parties would accept it or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
