<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sets Up Panel on Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
decided to set up a committee to examine the crisis over payment
of new minimum wage in the states.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Tuesday at a meeting of military state
administrators in Abuja, the federal capital, presided by the
Head of State, General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the media after the meeting, Lagos State
Administrator Colonel Mohammed Marwa said the issue of pay parity
among federal and state civil servants was high on the agenda of
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee will submit its report within the month,
adding that before any decision is taken, the administrators have
been ordered to continue negotiating with labor unions.
</P>
<P>
The Abubakar government announced a large-scale salary
increase for federal civil servants starting from September,
including raising the minimum wage from 2,200 Naira (about 25
U.S. Dollars) to 52,000 Naira (about 60 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the new salary package does not benefit state civil
servants, as the federal government said their payment should be
decided by state governments.
</P>
<P>
The move has sparked off unrest among state government
workers, who demanded the same minimum wage as their federal
counterparts, and in some cases, have turned to strike to press
their demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
