<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Disputes In Southern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of labor disputes in
China's Guangdong Province has been increasing since 1995,
affecting the local stable social and economic development,
Guangdong-Hong Kong Information Daily reported recently.
</P>
<P>
There were some 10,000 labor disputes annually from 1991 to
1994, but since 1995, the number has doubled and they have become
even more common in Guangdong. The number went from 927 in 1995 to
1,504 in 1997, and more workers are going in groups to government
departments to voice their complaints.
</P>
<P>
The disputes center on delayed payment of salaries, bad working
and living conditions, overtime without extra pay, on-the-job
injuries, and workers moving to another company with business
secrets. The newspaper quoted a government official as saying that
they were caused mainly by the Asian financial crisis, which
forced some foreign-funded or export-oriented companies to reduce
their workload or close down. The majority occur in private
companies and foreign-funded ones, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 740,000 work days were lost because of
strikes in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Some bosses simply fled across the border when the disputes
occurred, leaving behind some cheap equipment and tremendous
problems of calming down strikers, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The government finds itself less prepared to deal with such
large-scale disputes at a time when the labor laws and regulations
are not that mature, the paper said. And many times, the
government has to dig into its own pocket to settle the disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0095 </DOCNO>
