<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Giving Private Sector More Room (1) Eds: repeat for corrections in the first three paras. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese foreign trade
official said here today that private enterprises in China will be
granted the right to import and export directly, as of January 1.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say that the importance of the move is not
limited to the private sector's right of direct export and import
itself, it also shows that the private economy has much greater
room for development.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade was dominated by state-owned foreign
trade companies until the 1980s, when other state-owned large and
medium-sized enterprises gradually began to enter the business,
but private enterprises still have to go through state-owned
foreign trade companies in import and export trade.
</P>
<P>
Allowing private enterprises to get involved in the business is
just one of a series of government policies supporting the private
economy.
</P>
<P>
A senior State Economic and Trade Commission official said that
China will soon introduce a number of policies that help fund
raising, technical innovations, and personnel training for small
and medium-sized enterprises, which will put all enterprises on an
equal footing, regardless of their form of ownership, so as to
create fairer competition environment for the sake of small and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In addition to central government support, more policies are
coming from local governments to encourage the private economy.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province has adopted measures to encourage the merger
and acquisition of state- and collectively-owned enterprises by
private enterprises, while Guangdong Province has policies lifting
all restrictions on private enterprises in their operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Urges to Adopt New U.N. Resolution on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Wednesday urged U.N. Security Council to adopt a new resolution
on Kosovo in a bid to back up a U.S.-Yugoslav deal on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is the current president of the U.N. Security
Council, told BBC Radio that Britain would push for such a resolution
as NATO did not trust Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Cook was of the view that if the U.N. Security Council endorses
this agreement it would "make it plain to Milosevic that if he
breaks the agreement he is taking on the whole of the U.N., not
just NATO."
</P>
<P>
"I think we should make it clear ... any deviation, any breach
of compliance will provoke NATO to return to pressure on President
Milosevic," he said. 
</P>
