<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Giving Private Sector More Room (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Economist Lin Jiabin said that, with the growing government
support and more diverse market demand, China's private economy
has new opportunities and more room for development.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the reforms and opening up 20 years ago,
China's private economy, which started in the service sector, has
developed rapidly into almost every part of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
According to recent government statistics, China has near
30,000,000 private and individual businesses, employing some
70,000,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses not only are growing in size, but developing
into export-oriented, technology-intensive enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the added value of industrial goods
accounted for 17.4 percent, and consumer goods for 37 percent, of
total sales in their respective areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qizai, of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, said
that China's private economy has become a major force for economic
stability, as the state-owned enterprises are reformed.
</P>
<P>
But economists also say that China's private economy has not
truly been given enough national backing and the environment in
which it can compete fairly with the government-owned companies
has not been created.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is extremely important for the government to
provide supporting policies for the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Develop Anti-missile System in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States Defense
Secretary William Cohen has voiced Washington's readiness to
cooperate with the Gulf states to develop anti-missile rocket
launchers, the Kuwait News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After talks Tuesday in Riyadh with Saudi Defense Minister
Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz, Cohen said that due to the spreading
missile technology in the Middle East, an anti-missile rocket
launching system must be established to protect the interests of
the U.S. and the Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the news agency said that Prince Sultan denied that
he has discussed with Cohen any potential missile defense network
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that his talks with Prince Sultan covered issues
including the U.S. policy toward the security in the Gulf, the
situation in Iraq, and regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under inspections by the United Nations arms
experts to oversee the dismantlement of its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Cohen reiterated U.S. commitment to the security of the Gulf,
stressing that Washington is determined to force Iraq comply with
the U.N. resolutions regarding its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official arrived in Saudi Arabia Tuesday on the last
leg of his Gulf tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
