<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India, Pakistan Resume Talks Amid Mutual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- India and Pakistan are
scheduled to resume talks Thursday in Islamabad after suspension
of exactly 13 months amid mutual suspicion and with little hope
for any breakthrough especially on Kashmir, the most contentious
issue between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been tense after the
nuclear tests first by India and then by Pakistan in May this
year, which Pakistan said have further internationalized the
Kashmir dispute that India has insisted as a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
The strained relations further deteriorated the following
reports days ago that India is going to stage a large-scale
military exercise near the Pakistan border which evoked strong
reaction from Islamabad accusing New Delhi of vitiating the
atmosphere on the eve of the foreign secretary-level talks.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Pakistani Foreign Ministry said Tuesday that
Islamabad was extremely disturbed by the reports (of Indian
military exercises) particularly by the reported nature, size and
timing of these exercises.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had already taken up this matter with India and its
High Commissioner Satish Chandra had been told about the Pakistani
concerns, the spokesman told newsmen in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
However, Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes said Tuesday
that the exercises posed no concern to any nation as such
maneuvers were routine with all countries.
</P>
<P>
Western observers are reportedly alarmed at India's plan for
the exercises with 100,000 troops on its border with Pakistan and
they fear that India "might use the exercise to launch an
airstrike against a militant training camp in Pakistan Kashmir".
</P>
<P>
Under such an atmosphere, Indian Foreign Secretary K. Raghunath
leaves for Islamabad Thursday for talks with his Pakistani
counterpart Shamshad Ahmad on peace and security including
confidence building measures and Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India's External Affairs Ministry said Tuesday that New Delhi
was looking forward to resumption of the foreign secretary-level
talks with an "open mind" while Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz said frankly that no major breakthrough was expected from
these meetings.
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times said Wednesday that New Delhi appeared to
be determined to squash any attempt to dovetail the talks to its
current dialogue with the United States and other interlocutors on
the nuclear proliferation regime.
</P>
<P>
Judging by the attitude of the two sides on the eve of the
talks, there is remote possibility of any major progress as the
Kashmir issue, which had led to the breakdown of the talks 13
months ago, continues to be the dividing point as was evident from
the strong statements issued from both New Delhi and Islamabad
recently.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan declared Tuesday that it would speak on behalf of
Kashmir people while India dubbed the statement as utterly absurd
and stressed that Kashmir remains an integral part of India.
</P>
<P>
Jammu and Kashmir is one of the two issues scheduled to be
taken up for discussion during the Islamabad round of the talks
between the two countries while the other identified six issues
will be discussed during talks in New Delhi from November 5 to 13.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Favors Thai Official as WTO's New Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This showed support for the Thai government's continued
commitment to open-market policies, German Ambassador to Bangkok
Hermann Erath said in a speech available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The new government in Germany is still formulating its policy
and it will be clearer later. But from our viewpoint we would want
to see Dr. Supachai as the new director-general," Hermann told a
just-concluded German-Thai Chamber of Commerce meeting.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has launched an international campaign to promote the
appointment of Supachai as WTO's new chief.
</P>
<P>
Hermann, who took up his position recently, said Germany wanted
to raise its profile in terms of supporting the international rule
of law and free flow of goods and capital.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to keep a special focus on Asia and stick to our
well-designed long-term Asian strategy as the region will one day
be a powerhouse for the world again," he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany, he said, would strengthen its businesses' foothold in
key markets in Southeast Asia and, in particular, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Hermann said a survey of German companies already present in
Thailand revealed that 93 percent were prepared to increase
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged Europe to create robust domestic demand for products
that would fuel growth in Asia, thereby providing the same kind of
benefits that usually flowed from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The global economy required a reliable framework for the flow
of capital, he said. Bringing interest rates into line throughout
the European Union (EU) would help.
</P>
<P>
Germany has the world's third largest economy and is expected
to take up the EU presidency on January 1 next year. The EU has
about 290 million consumers and accounts for 19 percent of world
economic output and nearly 20 percent of global trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
