<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prince Ranariddh Proposes Holding Three-Party Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's FUNCINPEC party
President Prince Ranariddh suggested Wednesday that the three
party summit be held in Beijing, China.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to his father King Norodom Sihanouk, Ranariddh
requested the monarch to call the summit in the king's residence
in Beijing at an appropriate time. He insisted safety and
neutrality could not be assured for them at the present time in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The king responded that he will consult with Cambodian People's
Party (CPP) President Chea Sim and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen,
also the vice president of CPP, about the location of the summit.
"It must be agreed by all three parties," the monarch stressed.
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk returned to the capital last week for the first
time in nine months and postponed his trip to Beijing for medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
It was believed the king will leave here for Beijing after his
76th birthday on October 31.
</P>
<P>
However, the royal government of Cambodia did not favor the
plan to hold the summit outside the country.
</P>
<P>
"The government does not agree to hold summit outside the
country because ours is a sovereign state, and it's a Khmer issue,
so it should be held in our own country," government spokesman
Sieng Lapresse said Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The ruling CPP also wants the summit to be held inside the
country.
</P>
<P>
But Khieu Kanharith, CPP spokesman, told Xinhua Wednesday
afternoon, "The CPP supports the position of the government. But
if the king wishes to convene any summit outside the country, we
will follow his decision."
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, president of opposition Sam Rainsy Party (SRP),
Sunday also suggested a summit should be held on "neutral ground",
such as Beijing, where the king is due to have medical treatment,
or other alternative place like Tokyo, Paris and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Sieng Lapresse stressed that the situation in Cambodia now is
greatly different from the year 1979 to year 1993, during which
there was a war. After the 1993 election, the sovereignty of the
state had been restored and "we have the king to lead the
country".
</P>
<P>
"Another reason why the government insists holding the summit
in the country, is to save money. Cambodia right now is still very
poor. Many people are suffering from hunger," he added.
</P>
<P>
The hoped-for summit, which would be the second called by King
Sihanouk since the July 26 election, is aimed at breaking the
current deadlock and coming to an agreement to form a government
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The CPP won the elections, gaining a slim majority in the
National Assembly, but lacks the two-third majority needed to form
a new government. Two opposition parties, FUNCINPEC and the SRP,
in parliament have refused to join a coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Important Step Toward Peace in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian government has
proposed a far-reaching package of measures for a political
solution to the crisis in Kosovo, an important step toward
stability and peace in the province.
</P>
<P>
According to the political plan, announced by Serbian President
Milan Milutinovic at a cabinet meeting Tuesday evening, the
Kosovars can have self-rule and a free election will be held
within nine months to establish local authorities to govern
themselves.
</P>
<P>
"The citizens of Kosovo will realize democratic self-rule
through parliamentary, executive and judicial organs of authority
in Kosovo," Milutinovic said at the session which endorsed the
agreement reached earlier in the day by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which averted a possible military
operation by NATO, the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe (OSCE) is expected to send personnel to monitor the
situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE officials will travel to Belgrade later this week to
sign the agreement with President Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
According to the political solution, a local police force will be
established, reflecting the ethnic balance of the province, where
90 percent of the population is Albanian.
</P>
<P>
The crisis of Kosovo has haunted the Balkan region since the
Kosovo Liberation Army took up arms to fight for an independent
Kosovo seven months ago. To quell down the rebellion, the Serbian
government has sent thousands of troops into its southern province
to maintain the territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
A local analyst said the political framework was seen as a
proof to the international community and to Kosovar Albanians that
Belgrade intends to implement the agreement announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which guarantees the withdrawal of Serbian
security forces from Kosovo and the deployment of 2,000 OSCE
verification force in the region, is designed to help thousands of
ethnic Albanians who fled their home during the seven-month
conflict.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 refugees and displaced people can return home
and the international aid agencies can have freedom of movement
and carry on their humanitarian work without obstruction.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has received welcome at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
President Milosevic said the agreement was important to the
country as it "averts the danger of a military intervention
against our country."
</P>
<P>
"I'm really happy the crisis has been solved by peaceful means
with the maintenance of our territorial integrity," a Yugoslav
government official said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said the agreement could "lead to
the peaceful resolution of a crisis that threatens stability in
the Balkans and the lives of tens of thousands of refugees, many
of them homeless."
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said, "We welcome the
progress which has been made but there is a lot to be done yet."
</P>
<P>
Russian Presidential Press Secretary Dmitry Yakushkin said in a
statement that "Russia's aim remains the same - a political
solution of the problem, and there is now more optimism about the
possibility of success."
</P>
<P>
After all, Kosovo crisis is a domestic affairs and in the long
run, everything will depend on the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians
to decide their fate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lao PM On Fulfilling 1998-1999 Socio-Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Lao Prime Minister Sisavath
Keobounphanh has called on his government and local
administrations to fulfill the 1998-1999 socio-economic
development plan, Lao official news agency KPL reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the call Monday during a two-day
meeting on the implementation of the socio-economic development
plan and the budgetary plan for the 1998-1999 period.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by government ministers, presidents of
organizations, governors of provinces, the mayor of Vientiane
prefecture, and the chief of the special zone of Saysomboune.
</P>
<P>
Sisavath Keobounphanh said that the materialization of the
socio-economic development plan and the budgetary plan will
demonstrate the capacity and attention of the government, local
administrations, finance and planning officials as well as civil
servants in discharging their duties.
</P>
<P>
At present, the prime minister said, the people are facing
serious difficulties due to the rising cost of living. The people
have pinned their hopes on the government to take measures to
tackle the problems and improve the economic situation,
particularly to curb inflation, stabilize prices and foreign
exchange rates, and expand domestic production.
</P>
<P>
He said if the government achieves the targets of the 1998-1999
socio-economic development plan and budgetary plan, it means that
the government has fulfilled its promise to the people and
succeeded in leading the nation forward. And that will convince
the people and businessmen and merchants as well as international
organizations and foreign countries so that they may render more
assistance and support to the Lao government, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
