<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Pit Discovered Near Large Chinese Mausoleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A 120-m. by 110-m. pit full of
stone armors has been discovered by Chinese archaeologists near the
mausoleum of China's first emperor, Qinshihuang (259 - 210 BC), at
the largest ancient mausoleum in the world in Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists believe that the pit, which is about 500 meters
from the Mausoleum, was a copy of an arsenal built under the
Mausoleum for the terracotta figures who were imperial guards of
the emperor.
</P>
<P>
Farmers found the pit when the ground in an orchard subsided
when fruit trees were watered and archaeologists dug about 13
meters deep in the western part. It is about the size of pit No.1
of the terracotta warriors and has partitions rammed into the
earth and ashes of wood. The digging also brought up traces of
human activities, like red burnt soil, board ashes, and rammed
earth.
</P>
<P>
The stone armor is burnished and rectangular, round, elliptic,
and trapezoidal, with small holes drilled in two sides. Thin, flat
bronze thread was used to string the pieces together. Some armor
is fine and close, which archaeologists believe means that it was
for high-ranking military officers. Other crude armors were for
ordinary soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Ancient armor was usually made of leather or metal. Stone armor
has never been found in Shaanxi Province and rarely in China.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists also discovered bronze arrowheads and chariot
ornaments. They have never seen any historical documents about the
pit and were both surprised and puzzled by the latest discovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
