<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Commercial Ship Catches Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Latest reports from the
natural port of Blayo, 50 km west of the Somali port town of
Bossaso where a commercial vessel caught fire, said Wednesday
morning that the ship is still burning but has not sunk.
</P>
<P>
The vessel caught fire Tuesday when Somali businessmen were
loading coal on the ship for exporting illegally to Saudi Arabia,
the VHF radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports monitored here, huge and dark smoke
could be seen in Bossaso town Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of its crew members were brought to safety, while
four others including the captain of the ship, Jamal Salah,
remain missing. Thirteen of the crew were Sudanese, two Indians
and one Somali.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people including militiamen got on to the ship
forcefully and started looting all they could, especially the
electronic equipment aboard.
</P>
<P>
People in the area believe the missing crew were taken away by
gunmen in the area possibly in an attempt to demand a ransom for
their safe release. However, there's no word as yet concerning
their whereabouts as many businessmen and elders from the area
are trying hard to locate them.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the fire is not stated. However, speculations
are that it was deliberately blazed following a serious quarrel
between the Somali businessmen over the quota shares each man
would have on the ship.
</P>
<P>
The fire has started after more than 50,000 quintals of coal
were loaded onto the ship for Saudi Arabia. Many people believed
the ship could have been saved if the militiamen and other
looters did not storm into the ship.
</P>
<P>
Just like the ban on export of wild and female animals, coal
export was made illegal by the Bossaso authorities early last
year.
</P>
<P>
However the exercise did not stop but was moved to the natural
ports in the region and down to southern Somalia especially in
those ports controlled by faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed where
the coal is being exported more than anything else. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
