<HEADLINE> Ankara-Damascus Tension Easing off: Iranian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has said the tension between Syria and Turkey is easing
off following the mediation by Egypt and Iran, the official news
agency IRNA reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi told local media Tuesday night that the efforts made
by Egypt and Iran are bearing fruit in getting the two neighbors
to show flexibility toward solving their disputes.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has sent messages to his
Turkish and Syrian counterparts, helping them see eye to eye on
peaceful solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of sheltering rebels of its outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) fighting since 1984 for an
independent state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has demanded that Damascus extradite PKK leaders and
close alleged PKK camps in the Syrian-controlled Beqaa valley of
Lebanon. To exert pressure, it has reportedly massed troops on the
Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
Syria has denied harboring Turkey's Kurdish militants.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi voiced Iran's readiness to continue its efforts to see
Syria and Turkey, both members of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC), exchanging views directly.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister shuttled between Damascus and
Ankara last week in a bid to seek a peace solution to their row.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which is holding OIC presidency, has urged the two Muslim
countries to settle their disputes through political means in
order not to give opportunities to Islam's enemies to use the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
