<HEADLINE> Samsonov Predicts China's Victory in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, Guangdong Province, October 14 (Xinhua) -- World
top-ranked
table tennis player Vladimir Samsonov said that China would cash
in on home-court advantage to win the men's World Cup tournanent.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup, which starts on Thursday, will see 16 elite
players vie for 38,000 U.S. dollars champion's purse. Five of
this year's participants have won the annual event.
</P>
<P>
"China is odds-on favorite for this title," said Samsonov from
Belarus. "I will be happy with a semi-final spot."
</P>
<P>
Kong Linghui, world champion and World Cup winner in 1995,
will lead teammates Liu Guoliang and Ma Lin to face assaults from
Europe. Liu was 1996 Olympic and World Cup champion while Ma was
Malaysian Open winner this year.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, who added European Masters Cup, Croatian Open title
and European Top 12 crown to his European championship this year,
tipped two-time World Cup winner Zoran Primorac and reigning
world champion Jan-Ove Waldner as other title hofefuls.
</P>
<P>
"Primorac's backhand is the best in the world and Waldner has
battle experience and deceptive serve." said Samsonov. "Both are
very difficult to deal with."
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, Primorac and Waldner, the trio who shut out Chinese
from the singles title clash in last year's world championships,
are the biggest threats to host players here, admitted Chinese
head coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
"Three Tigers hold us in awe more or less and they are our
targets," Cai said, referring to the European top trio.
</P>
<P>
"There exists a gap between Chinese players and Three Tigers,
both technically and mentally, and we will have to catch up with
them before the world championships next year," Cai added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the nickname that Chinese gave him, Samsonov
said: "I've never heard of it. It's sort of funny, but I like it."
</P>
<P>
Former world number one Jean-Michel Saive (Belgium), 1993
world champion Jean-Philippe Gatien (France), Kim Taek Soo (South
Korea),Kalinikos Kreanga (Greece), Jorg Rosskopf (Germany), Peter
Karlsson(Sweden) and Johnny Huang (Canada) are the players who
might not win the title but could cause upsets.
</P>
<P>
At the other end of spectrum are continental champions Liu
Song (Argentina), Mark Smythe (Australia) and Au Saleh Ahmed
(Egypt). 
</P>
</TEXT>
