<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Annual Inflation Rate Tops 27.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The increase in the prices of
various foodstuffs in recent months has affected Zambia's annual
inflation rate which has grown from 27.1 percent in August to
27.5 percent by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Wednesday quoted latest statistics released by
Bank of Zambia as saying the inflation levels rose marginally
because of the increase in the prices of maize meal, meat, eggs,
fresh fish, cereal and cereal products.
</P>
<P>
Further increases were recorded in the prices of tobacco,
cement and charcoal.
</P>
<P>
The increase appears to have tilted the Zambian government's
earlier predictions to close the year at nine percent inflation
rate and to enhance the gross domestic product (GDP) growth by
five percent.
</P>
<P>
Now the country's central bank hopes to reduce the inflation
rate toward a macro-economic target of 15 percent and to
guarantee that the GDP growth rate can reach 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The situation, however, has been aggravated by the donors
withholding their balance of payments support compounded by low
export earnings from copper and the non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
The donors have not released their pledged aid to Zambia,
saying the country can only receive the money after it privatizes
the remaining assets of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM), the traditional foreign exchange earner and financial
pillar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
