<HEADLINE> Central China's Henan Outlines Power Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Henan Province in central
China will give equal emphasis to the upgrading of existing power
plants and the building of power grids over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The province will build six new power plants with an aggregate
generating capacity of 4.3 million kw over the coming years.
Feasibility reports on the construction of the new plants have won
state approval, according to information from the Provincial
Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
It will take five years to complete power-grid upgrading in the
province's urban areas, and three years to complete power-grid
construction and upgrading in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
An official with the commission said they warmly welcome
overseas investors' participation in the province's power
development plan, while at the same time they strive for more
funding from the state.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, Henan had a combined generating capacity of 11.72
million kw. The total generating capacity of the province is
expected to rise to 13 million kw by the end of this year, 15
million kw by 2000, and 17 million kw by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The province is now constructing six power plants, and by the
end of this year two million kw will be added to its total
generating capacity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
