<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's delayed mines sale Concerned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Association of Chambers
of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI) is worried that another quarter
of the year has gone without positive resolution on the sale of
Nkana and Nchanga mines because this is only prolonging business
pessimism and low activity.
</P>
<P>
Daily Mail Wednesday quoted ZACCI chief Gerry Chabwera as
saying that the delay in the sale of mines will further delay the
release of balance of payment support which is critical to the
stability of the exchange rate of Zambia's currency.
</P>
<P>
"Government is forced to draw upon its meager resources to
meet commitments that will otherwise be funded by aid and this
exacerbates a serious funding gap. That deficit contributes to
rising interest rates, which worsen the economic environment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Chabwera said that Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) and
the government's severe cash flow problems, their non-payment and
delayed payment of creditors have been the major factor in the
liquidity crunch which is causing economic recession.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM said in its latest half-year report that it had a loss of
126.6 billion Kwacha (about 63 million U.S. Dollars) as compared
to last year's 17.9 billion Kwacha (about nine million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
He also expressed concern at the late arrival of fertilizer
for the forthcoming farming season.
</P>
<P>
He further said employment creation, investment promotion and
the stimulation of both local and foreign demand for Zambian
products are crucial to the revival of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Last May donors pledged to provide Zambia with an aid of 530
million Dollars at the Consultative Group meeting held Paris.
However, Germany and the Netherlands has made it clear that they
will not release the pledged aid until the completion of the
privatization of the ZCCM, which earns more than 80 percent of
Zambia's foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
German ambassador Helmuth Schroeder to Zambia said that it
will be economically imprudent if the assistance is released
before the privatization process of ZCCM is completed.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Money ZCCM is losing equals to the
amount of the aid the donor community pledged to give Zambia and
that if it is released, it will have no impact on its economy and
serve no purpose because all of it will go to bailing out the
ailing ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has been trying to quicken the
privatization of ZCCM but failed to complete the process in the
first half of this year as planned.
</P>
<P>
Due to disagreement over the cost of Nkana and Nchanga mines,
two biggest mines of country, Zambia discontinued the
negotiations with the Kafue consortium last April over the sale
of the two mines, which accounts for 65 percent of ZCCM assets.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown not only affects ZCCM itself but affects other
sectors as well which had links with ZCCM. ZCCM has cut down its
orders of various manufactured goods. Output of the manufacturing
sector decreased by 10 percent to 15 percent in the first four
months this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
