<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Dropping in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued falling in
Tokyo Wednesday on fears that a government plan to refuel
capital-short major banks may fail to ease the country's severe
credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 172.06 points, or 1.30
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 13,070.73.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, sank 14.80 points or 1.48 percent to 984.18.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to about 358 million
shares from Tuesday's 506.62 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nissho Iwai Corp. was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Bank and brokerage shares led the decline, while domestic demand
sectors, including steel and construction, also slumped. But
export-linked automobile and precision instrument shares rebounded on
buybacks following their sharp declines last week on the surging yen.
</P>
<P>
Analysts voiced skepticism about whether the government's bank
bailout plan, which doubled the amount of available public funds from
30 trillion yen (about 252.1 billion dollars) to 60 trillion yen
(about 504.2 billion dollars), would spur banks to ask for a capital
refueling.
</P>
<P>
A bank which asks for a capital boost may be required to have its
executives step down. According to news reports, applicant banks must
submit plans to "clarify management's responsibility" for their
bad-loan problems.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,344 issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 777 to 330, with 177 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
