<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Study Suggests Cancer Often Undiagnosed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A study of autopsy results
at a U.S. hospital found that cancer was often missed or
misdiagnosed by doctors.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the latest issue of the Journal of the
American Medical Association, said a team of researchers reviewed
the records of more than 1,100 people autopsied at the Louisiana
State University Medical Center in New Orleans between 1986 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
Autopsies found 250 malignant tumors in 225 patients, but
clinicians had correctly diagnosed only 56 percent of these
tumors, according to the researchers, led by Dr. Elizabeth
C. Burton.
</P>
<P>
"One hundred eleven malignant neoplasms in 100 patients, or 44
percent of cases, had been either undiagnosed or misdiagnosed,"
Burton and colleagues write.
</P>
<P>
They said that they focused on cancer diagnoses, but it is
likely that other diseases and disorders were also misdiagnosed or
undiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
The researchers urged to revive the long-abandoned practice of
performing routine autopsies in U.S. hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Autopsies often are done when death results from accident, foul
play or when cause of death is a mystery. However, the procedure
is performed only 5-10 percent in teaching hospitals today,
compared to 50 percent in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Some clinicians argued that technological advances have made
clinical diagnoses more accurate, and thereby made postmortem
diagnoses less essential.
</P>
<P>
But Burton and colleagues conclude that their findings
underscore the value of autopsies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
