<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Telecom Dismayed By Cold Reception Of Discount Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China Telecom has expressed
disappointment over poor market reception of its offer of 70
percent discounts for domestic direct dial (DDD) telephone calls,
according to today's Beijing Daily.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom started a 70 percent discount for DDD calls made
from midnight to 7 am, beginning on July 1 until June 30, 1999,
assuming that business volume would surge with customers taking
advantage of the cheaper rate.
</P>
<P>
However, the offer generated a volume rise of only 25 percent
in the first three months, a rate called "meager" by the
state-owned company.
</P>
<P>
To discover why, the company conducted a sample survey of 100
customers. They said they would not call anyone during the
70-percent-discounted hours, while 50 percent of them would make
calls between 9 pm and midnight, when a 50 percent discount is
offered.
</P>
<P>
They said both the caller and the person being called should be
sleeping in the midnight-to-7-am period and it is particularly
impolite to call someone so late.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it believes the company will revoke the
discount if the market continues to turn a cold back on this offer
after the one-year trial period expires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
