<HEADLINE> Swedish Telecom Giant Helps Beijing Students Go On-line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Students at four middle schools
in this Chinese capital can now browse the Internet, thanks to an
educational project financed by the world telecom giant Erricson
(China) company.
</P>
<P>
Built at a cost of over one-million yuan (about 120,000 U.S.
dollars), the Erricson Telecom Space Station can now be accessed at
two middle schools attached to the Beijing Normal University,
Beijing No.2 Middle School and the Middle School Attached to the
Beijing Communications University.
</P>
<P>
The stations are equiped with computers and advanced
telecommunication facilities, in addition to a series of
educational software, books on popular sciences and
state-of-the-art telecommunication products, according to Michael
Ricks, chief executive officer with Erricson (China).
</P>
<P>
The Swiss-based multinational has set up nine joint
ventures and 23 offices in China since it first entered the
country in 1994.  
</P>
