<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Vet Treats Orangutans With Hepatitis C in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian veterinarian has
successfully treated an orangutan suffering from Hepatitis C at a
research center in Indonesia's East Kalimantan province and is
treating 11 more orangutans.
</P>
<P>
"We were delighted with Dr. Header Davis' success and we hope
that he would be able to treat the other orangutans," the
Wanariset Sambodja Research Center's head Adi Susilo said.
</P>
<P>
Susilo said he did not know what drugs Dr. Davis used.
</P>
<P>
"What was obvious was his tirelessness in treating the
orangutans," he was quoted by Antara News Agency Wednesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the 11 orangutans still suffering from Hepatitis
C were quarantined in an area surrounded by a 1.5-meter wall to
prevent the disease from spreading.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that this disease does not spread easily. But there
is a chance the sick orangutans could transmit the disease if they
come into contact with the healthy orangutans -- even with human
beings," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some diseases may affect both orangutans and human beings.
These include diarrhea, flu and cough, he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
