<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supermarkets Gaining Popularity in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Supermarkets in this economic
and financial center of China have become the most frequently
patronized places for the purchase of food and daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Some 67 percent of Shanghai residents buy food, beverages and
pastry at supermarkets, while 66 percent of the residents buy
other daily necessities in them, according to an official survey
conducted by the municipal statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
Many of the survey respondents say they choose to go to
supermarkets for these items because of cheaper prices, more
varieties and convenience.
</P>
<P>
Supermarkets first appeared in Shanghai in the early 1990s and
have gained popularity amid rapid expansion in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the 28 chain-store supermarkets in
Shanghai had a combined 8.1 billion yuan in retail sales last
year, about 6 percent of the city's total retail sales of
consumer goods in 1997. The retail sales volume of
these supermarkets, which have more than 1,000 outlets and 24,000
employees, exceeded 10 billion yuan in the first nine months
this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say that supermarket sales of food and daily
necessities now face fierce competition and have limited room for
further expansion, but sales of building materials, household
electric appliances and children's goods still have bright
prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Conservation Vital to Keep Yellow River Flowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are pointing
out that water conservation and long-term diversion projects are
vital for maintaining the uninterrupted flow of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The worsening drought on the lower reaches of the river has
attracted nationwide attention, as scientists from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS) visited four provinces on the lower and
middle reaches of the river in July to document existing
problems. They warn that interrupted flow may result in disastrous
floods and drought in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"Water conservation should be the current measure to ease the
shortage of water resources in the valley, especially in irrigated
areas relying on water drawn from the river," said CAS academician
Liu Changming.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the water pumped from the river is used
for agricultural irrigation, but outdated diversion facilities and
irrigation methods has resulted in a low water utilization rate of
25 percent, compared with 50 percent in areas irrigated by well
water.
</P>
<P>
Experts have suggested raising water prices according to
quality and quantity so that a sense of water conservation can be
established. At the same time, the recycling rate of water for
industrial purpose must be increased with more industrial waste
water disposed.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that most parts of the river valley are arid areas
without much rainfall. "Considered from a long-term point of view,
diversion projects are necessary to supply water to the Yellow
River," he added.
</P>
<P>
A plan proposed in 1950s envisioned channeling water from the
Yangtze, China's longest river, to northern areas and to the
course of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that one idea gaining wide acceptance is boring
tunnels to channel water from the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River, or the Tongtian, Yalong and Dadu rivers, into the upper
reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Another idea is to channel the Daning River, a tributary of the
middle reaches of the Yangtze, northward into the Yellow River
near the central China city of Zhengzhou.
</P>
<P>
Even though these large-scale projects will need huge
investments and involve technical problems, Liu urged a
feasibility study and preparatory work on these projects as soon
as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Jiangsu Anticipates Record Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Total output from this year's rice acreage of 2.4 million
hectares will exceed 20 billion kilos, over 500 million kilos more
than last year, the provincial agricultural department predicted.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, unit yield will surpass 8,250 kilos per
hectare, 150 kilos more than last year.
</P>
<P>
Both total output and per unit yield will top historical highs,
the department said.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the anticipated record-high rice production
to the spread of new farming techniques and better species.
</P>
</TEXT>
