<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Offshore Oilfields In China's Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists have
discovered three medium-sized oilfields at Shijiutuo in Bohai Bay
with 60 million tons of proven oil reserves and 8 billion cubic
meters of gas, an official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
During recent trial operations, they produced 310,000 cu.m. of
gas and 190 cu.m. of oil a day, making Shijiutuo the largest
offshore oil producer in China. It has more than 300 million tons
of proven reserves, said Deng Yunhua, a geologist there.
</P>
<P>
Shijiutuo covers 600 sq. km. in central Bohai Bay, 100 km. from
Tanggu Port and 20 km. from Jingtang Harbor. All 5 oilfields in
the region produce heavy oil, buried in a layer from 20 m. to 60
m. thick.
</P>
<P>
The China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC) and the
U.S. Texaco and ARCO are planning to undertake oil exploration in
the Qinhuangdao 32-6 oilfield, which has a production period of 20
years.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC will do the actual exploration and the two U.S. companies
will play a supporting role. The Chinese will be responsible for
51 percent of the cost, with the remainder being covered by the
two U.S. companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
