<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybean, Wheat Futures Prices Rise on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Corn, soybean and wheat
futures prices surged Tuesday following Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman's confirmation of a food aid package for Russia.
</P>
<P>
At the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, corn for delivery in
December was eight cents higher at 2.28 U.S. dollars a bushel;
November soybeans were 6.5 cents higher at 5.635 dollars a bushel;
December wheat was 5.75 cents higher at 2.96 dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
Glickman, who discussed food shortages with the Russian
ambassador last week, said that U.S. and Russian officials met
Tuesday to discuss an aid package.
</P>
<P>
"It is in our interest as a nation to provide help and
assistance" to Russia, which is faced with one of its worst
harvests in 40 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
There has been talk of food aid for Russia in recent weeks, so
the idea is not new. "But each time the market hears about it, the
prospects seem to solidify a little bit," said Don Roose,
president of U.S. Commodities Inc.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Russia is seeking up to 3.3 million
tons of donated grain from the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
