<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remote Xinjiang Becomes Haven for Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region has emerged as a haven for overseas investment in an
underdeveloped part of China.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern region has attracted some 400 overseas
companies from around the world to make use of its wool, cotton,
oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
Although the region was on an international trade route in
ancient times, its position declined in this century because of
its remoteness. This has been remedied, however, by the opening-up
drive and massive development in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The first overseas investors concentrated on tourism and food
and brought Kentucky Fired Chicken and Holiday Inn to the
region. The wool industry has also been a draw, with a Hong Kong
investor funding a spinning venture in the early 1980s in the
first overseas joint venture in China's textile industry.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, its grain, cotton and oil have become
attractive to investors from America, Europe, Southeast Asia and
countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funding has also helped reclaim 550,000 hectares of
waste land, or a third of the country's reclaimable waste
land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
