<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ordinary Chinese Farmer Becomes Multi-Millionaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China's rural policies in recent
years have turned a group of poor but diligent and hardworking
farmers into millionaires or even billionaires.
</P>
<P>
Han Wei, a 43-year-old chicken-farm owner in northeast China's
Liaoning Province, is one of them.
</P>
<P>
Impelled by the more flexible government policies, Han borrowed
3,000 yuan from his neighbors as capital to start a family chicken
farm in 1984.
</P>
<P>
"When we first set up the farm," he said, "all we had were the 50
chickens. My wife fed them in the courtyard as she carried our son on
her back. Sometimes, a mischievous chicken leapt on his head,
pecking at his hair."
</P>
<P>
Fourteen years later, the 50 chickens have become 1.5
million. And Han's fixed assets have soared to 500 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Now the entire process, including feeding, excrement cleaning,
coop-temperature regulation and sterilization has all been
automated.
</P>
<P>
As raising chickens involves genetics and a knowledge of
nutrition, environment and management, Han has invited experts
from both China and abroad to offer technical guidance. He also
obtains information from the Internet each day and goes abroad
each year to survey the market.
</P>
<P>
He has opened more than 80 egg shops in Dalian, meeting half
that city's market demand.
</P>
<P>
With accumulated funds, Han has invested 130 million yuan to
set up a company dealing in rare Pacific seafood.
</P>
<P>
He also bought a three-room flat in downtown Dalian and a Mercedes
car, and plans to send his son and daughter abroad to study in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
"There would be no stunning success of today without economic
reforms and the Party's opening policy," Han said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the period of food shortages, Han said, "Eggs used to
be saved for women in confinement and rare guests in most
families. Even in major cities like Beijing and Shanghai, eggs
were rationed, 0.25 kg for each urban resident per month on
average."
</P>
<P>
"But now, eggs are a common food in both urban and rural
areas. The per capita annual consumption of eggs in Liaoning
averaged 24 kg last year," he added.
</P>
<P>
The welcome change derived from the national fundamental shift
from a planned economy to a market-oriented economy offers
excellent opportunities for industrious Chinese farmers who have
worked in the fields for generations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
