<HEADLINE> China's Prices Dropping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Retail Price Index
(RPI) rose one percent in September over the previous month,
mainly because of substantial price hikes for vegetables in
flood-hit areas of north China, said a report by the State
Statistics Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
Last month's RPI nevertheless registered a decrease of 3.3
percent from the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index for September rose 1.6 percent over
August, but decreased 1.5 percent from the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
For the January-September period, the RPI and CPI witnessed
decreases of 2.5 percent and 0.7 percent respectively. 
</P>
