<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Psychological Report Excerpts (2-Last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Neurological Evaluation:
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jeremy Schmahmann conducted a neurological examination of
Mr. Tyson, with consultation from Dr. Barry Jordan. In peparation
for the examination, Mr. Tyson underwent an EEG and MRI of the
brain. Both of these studies were normal. Mr. Tyson was found to
have a normal neurological evaluation. He did exhibit some
difficulties with "Working memory, sequencing and switching
sets...and some difficulty with perseveration... These findings,
minor though they are, are consistent with a problem of the
executive control system. There is no accompanying
electrophysiologic abnormality as shown by the EEG, or anatomic
abnormality as shown by the normal MRI."
</P>
<P>
The neuropsychological testing administered by Dr. Thomas
Deters indicated that Mr. Tyson is a man with a mixture of
cognitive strengths and weaknesses. His relative weaknesses are
in the areas of attention, short term/working memory, verbal
learning and memory, and fine motor coordination. He also has
deficits on some select measures of executive control. Dr. Deters
notes that Mr. Tyson has both emotional and executive control
problems. These executive control problems are not of such degree
that they would prevent Mr.Tyson from appropriate participation
in boxing if he is able to address his emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
Psychological Evaluation:
</P>
<P>
The results of the psychological evaluation conducted by Dr.
David Medoff revealed Mr. Tyson's moderate depression,
self-criticism, irritability, anger, individualism, and
difficulty in interpersonal relationships. His profile was
consistent with those of people who experiene anger and
irritability but are ordinarily able to control these feelings.
It also revealed a tendency to rely on others to a greater extent
than expected, as well as naivete in these relationships. The
testing did not suggest the presence of any major mental illness
or personality disorder. These findings are consistent with our
clinical observations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Law Enacted for Forest Protection in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province in south
China recently enacted a new regulation on forest land protection
and administration which requires licenses for the use of forest
land.
</P>
<P>
More than 73,000 hectares of forest land were converted to
development zones, real estate, and tourist sites between 1987 and
1996, half of this without the consent of the government.
</P>
<P>
Licenses will be issued by local governments to clarify the land's
property and utilization rights and work out approval procedures
for forest land use.
</P>
<P>
The regulation bans all forms of logging, and anyone
violating this regulation will be punished in accordance with
criminal law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
