<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Children Study in World-Roof School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Nearly all the children in Phari
Town on the roof of the world in the Tibet Autonomous Region are
able to study at the Qingpu Primary School free of charge because
of aid from Shanghai and the local government.
</P>
<P>
Tsedo, deputy headmaster of the primary school, said he is very
pleased to see the youngsters going to school every morning.
</P>
<P>
He said that among the 55 graduates this year, 43 entered the
Yadong County Middle School and five were selected to study in
other provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to Tsedo, 17 of the 19 teachers here are college or
polytechnic school graduates.
</P>
<P>
Phari Town, at an elevation of 4,370 meters, used to be sealed
by snow for more than five months a year due to poor transport and
telecommunication condition. And because of the poor education
facilities, many children worked as cowherd for their families
instead of going to school.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, the education department of Xigaze Prefecture invested
400,000 yuan to improve the teaching facilities there. And in 1996
Shanghai's Qingpu County offered 500,000 yuan to set up the Qingpu
Primary School.
</P>
<P>
The school now has 309 pupils in nine classes consisting of six
grades. Their tuition fees, 70 to 80 yuan per school year, are
paid by the government. The school offers some 10 subjects
including Chinese and Tibetan languages, mathematics, history,
music and physical culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
