<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Industrial Production Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- India's industrial production
registered a growth rate of only 2.4 percent in August compared
with the 5.2 percent in the same month last year but it showed a
marginal improvement compared with the 1.7 percent registered in
July.
</P>
<P>
Cumulative industrial growth this year (April to August) dipped
to 3.5 percent from the 5.5 percent in the previous year,
according to the latest figures for index of industrial production
(IIP).
</P>
<P>
The IIP released Tuesday by the Central Statistical
Organization showed that the cumulative growth in industrial
production has declined consistently during the current financial
year from 5.4 percent in April-June to 4 percent in April-July and
the present level of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Main reason behind the downslide was the poor performance of
the manufacturing sector which accounts for almost four-fifth of
the total weight of the IIP.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector recorded a growth of 2 percent in
August against the 4.8 percent during the same period last year.
So far in the year, the sector recorded a growth rate of 3.2
percent compared with the 5.4 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The decline in industrial growth was more evident in use-based
classification with capital goods and consumer goods segments
recording negative growth rates in August.
</P>
<P>
Capital goods segment recorded a negative growth rate of 1.6
percent against the 8.6 percent during the same period last year,
while consumer goods segment declined by 1 percent during the
month compared with the 4.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
From April to August, capital goods and consumer goods segments
recorded a growth of 4.8 percent and 1.7 percent respectively over
the same period the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Growth in mining sector also remained subdued during the month
at 0.6 percent compared with the 5.5 percent last year. The
cumulative growth during the period was low at 0.5 percent against
the 5 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Though the electricity sector posted an impressive growth of
7.5 percent in August, it was still below the 8.7 percent achieved
during the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumer non-durables registered a negative growth
rate of 1.5 percent in August against the 4.3 percent in the same
period last year, but the cumulative growth during April to August
stood at 1.9 percent compared with a negative growth rate of 0.3
percent for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Growth rate of consumer durables declined to 0.3 percent in
August this year compared with the 3.7 percent in the same month
in 1997 and the cumulative growth during April-August also
declined significantly to 0.6 percent against the 5.7 percent in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Monitoring Indian Economy (CMIE), an independent
forecaster, said Monday that growth rate of the Indian economy
would drop to 4.5 percent in 1998-99 from an earlier projection of
5 percent due to a decline in agricultural production and a
substantial slowdown in the industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
Growth rate in 1997-98 had also been revised downwards from 5.1
percent to 4.5 percent, according to CMIE's monthly review for
September.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is sharply lower than the 6.5 percent projected by
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), the central bank of the country,
and the government's expectation of 6.5 to 7 percent growth for
1998-99.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the Confederation of Indian Industry
(CII) also showed that the majority of Indian industries had less
than 10 percent or negative growth rate in the first half of the
current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The biggest slump had been experienced by the automobile sector
which saw a 41 percent dip in commercial vehicles production, 53
percent in middle and heavy commercial vehicles, 20 percent in
light commercial vehicle and three percent in cars.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the basic goods sector also remained depressed with
only 2.5 percent increase in aluminum, 5.4 percent in cement, 5.2
percent in fertilizer but the production of cold rolled steel and
lead and lead alloy decreased 2.5 and 13 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
CMIE's revised growth projections for 1998-99 indicate that the
service sector would grow at 6 percent against the earlier
forecast of 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
It has, however, increased its farm output growth forecast to
1.0 percent from 0.7 percent and industrial output growth to 4.5
percent from 4.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
