<HEADLINE> OSCE to Send Observers to Kosovo in 10 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) is to send 2,000 observers to Kosovo
in about ten days, OSCE Secretary-General Giancarlo Aragona said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Italian news agency ANSA, Aragona
said the mission to Kosovo is the OSCE's most important task since
its establishment in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The observers would leave for Kosovo soon after the OSCE's
permanent council in Vienna authorizes the action, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he would ask the 55 member countries to send civilian
staff and unarmed military personnel.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the observers' task was to verify
Yugoslavia's compliance with the United Nations Security Council
Resolution 1199, which includes an immediate ceasefire, a
withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo, a return of refugees, and
autonomy talks with ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the OSCE mission to Kosovo was reached between
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic earlier on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
