<HEADLINE> Italy to Participate in OSCE Observation Mission in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Italy will serve as a participant
in the mission to observe the troubled Serbian province of Kosovo
led by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) under a latest peace deal, Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dini hailed the significance of the deal brokered by U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke, under which Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has agreed to an OSCE ground verification of Belgrade's
compliance with the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Dini said diplomatic efforts to end the Kosovo conflict had
entered the last stage and expected agreement to be reached on
issues under discussion for a long-term solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the Italian foreign minister discussed the
Kosovo issue by telephone with his Russian counterpart Igor
Ivanov. They agreed on an immediate convening of the six-nation
Contact Group on the former Yugoslavia following the completion of
Holbrooke's mission, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Dini expressed appreciation for Russia's diplomatic efforts to
help solve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Italian Deputy Defense Minister Massimo Brutti said in a radio
speech on Tuesday that Italian forces were prepared to participate
in the military intervention over Kosovo by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
He noted however that pressure should be exerted on Yugoslavia
to obtain a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis as it was still
possible to open negotiations and dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
