<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Vietnam Seeks Internal Stability for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Economic Development
</P>
<P>
(BY Ling Dequan)
</P>
<P>
HANOI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of Vietnam
began Tuesday its sixth polonium, phase i, to review the
implementation of the country's socio-economic targets for this
year, and devise orientation and tasks for development for next
year.
</P>
<P>
As 1998 draws to a close, Vietnam's Communist Party and the
government have intensified efforts to meet the set economic
targets, focusing on internal measures to tackle growing obstacles
appearing on the economic horizon.
</P>
<P>
According to most Vietnamese economists, 1999 will be a tough
year in comparison to 1998.
</P>
<P>
The financial and monetary crisis has now spread over the
entire region, affecting small and established economies alike.
</P>
<P>
Several Vietnamese economists have predicted the fallout from
the crisis will impact heavily on the macro-economies of every
country in the Asia region with devastating consequences.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam acknowledges that its economy is still developing and,
therefore, is constrained by internal and external factors.
</P>
<P>
Economists warned that it is necessary for the government to
assess the situation and balance national development strategies
in order to channel available resources in the search for economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
Policy makers admitted that Vietnam cannot achieve the set
economic targets, even though most targets were lowered in July.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam Investment Review reported in its latest issue
that Vietnam could still achieve GDP growth of 6-7 percent for the
year, though down from the 9 percent growth target set at the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
In the same token, industrial growth could increase 10-11
percent (down from 13 percent forecast at the beginning of the
year), agricultural output could increase 3-3.5 percent (down from
4.6-4.8 percent), export growth could increase ten percent (down
from 25-26 percent), while year-on-year inflation may be less than
ten percent, not the seven percent as anticipated.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party and the government must now face the truth
and acknowledge that economic targets will not be achieved this
year. Alternative approaches to maintain economic stability have
now been raised and need serious executive consideration.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration the regional crisis which has
devastated the economies of many countries, several economists
argued that Vietnam's achievements should not be ignored and, in
some ways, can be viewed as a success.
</P>
<P>
Others argued, while it is true the country has suffered from
external factors largely outside Vietnam's control, the government
has dragged its heels in regard to economic reform and must
accelerate the process.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam should not view 1998 as a year of doom-and-gloom,
rather a year of mixed results", the English-language weekly
quoted leading economists and observers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Though most economists agreed Vietnam has made an enormous
progress, especially in maintaining political and social
stability, further steps must be taken to ensure Vietnam continues
along the path of integration with the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that major measures and adjustment for
the following years will be decided at the on-going sixth polonium
(phase 1) of the Communist Party of Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
