<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang's Urban Residents Have More Living Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The living conditions of urban
residents in east China's Zhejiang Province have improved
considerably over the past two decades, with per capita living
space doubled during the period.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's urban residents now have an average of 11.28 square
meters of living space per person, up from 5.5 square meters in
1978 when China launched the economic reform and
opening-up drive, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's housing construction sector has also developed
steadily in the last two decades. During the national Eighth
Five-Year Plan period (1991- 1995) alone, more than 25 million
square meters of run-down and unsafe houses were demolished, and
some 620,000 residents moved into new buildings.
</P>
<P>
In the provincial capital of Hangzhou, housing with a combined
floor space of 1.86 million square meters were constructed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While more commercial housing has been built in recent years,
Zhejiang has also stepped up efforts to build more economic
residences to cater to the needs of low-income families. More than
30,000 low-income families moved into new housing last year alone.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official said that Zhejiang will continue to take
measures to improve the living conditions of the urban residents.
</P>
<P>
Urban residents will have an average 12 square meters of living
space per person by the year 2000, according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit From Technical Training Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Though still a farmer, Huang
Yongjiang has become an agro-technician in the eyes of his fellow
villagers in Xinchang County in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Huang plants strawberries, grapes and honey peaches on some
three hectares of land, raises fish, and earns over 100,000 yuan a
year, a dozen times more than the average income of his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
What's more, he has implemented a research project on the
cultivation of strawberries in the county and spread the
techniques to local farmers.
</P>
<P>
Huang attributes his progress mostly to the technical training
he received in Japan in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"The experience not only allowed me access to some new
techniques, but also opened up my view," the 30-year-old farmer
said.
</P>
<P>
Like Huang, more and more Chinese farmers have in recent years
gone to foreign countries such as Japan, Singapore and Thailand on
their own for technical training in areas including agriculture,
machinery, electronics and clothing manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult to know how many farmers have gone abroad for
this purpose, but the number is on the rise," said Ye Zhengming,
director of the China Association for Promotion of Applied
Technology Exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Most of the farmers going abroad come from coastal areas such
as Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Fujian and Guangdong provinces, whose fast-
growing rural economies have prompted local farmers to improve
themselves, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
In Shaoxing County in Zhejiang, one of China's most developed
areas, township and village enterprises have been mushrooming and
some 30 farmers have gone to large companies in Japan for
technical training during the past five years. Twenty-seven have
returned to work in rural enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Jinliang is one example. After two years of technical training
in an auto factory in Japan, he came back to set up a silk-thread
plant which targets Europe as its market. This year, he became
deputy general manager of the Jishan Group, an enterprise group
estimated to have 100 million yuan in assets.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the overseas-trained farmers are now the backbone of
the managerial and technical class of the rural enterprises in
which they work," said Chen Zhiwei, director of the Shaoxing
Science and Technology Association.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of township and village enterprises in
coastal areas are now eyeing overseas technical training as an
effective way to improve the quality of their employees, and they
plan to send more of them abroad, Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
