<HEADLINE> Hungary Deliberating NATO's Request For Use of Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's request for permission to use Hungary's territorial
air space to coordinate air strikes against Yugoslavia is meeting
with varied responses in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, NATO, in its preparations for attacks against
Yugoslavia, asked for Hungary's permission to use its air space to
conduct military strikes against Yugoslavia. The request caused a
stir in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian government decided to grant NATO's request on
Tuesday and suggested the National Assembly endorse it at the
delayed special meeting on Wednesday. Related commissions under
the assembly are consulting intensively over the request.
</P>
<P>
Political parties, including the Hungarian Workers' Party,
strongly opposed their country's involvement in a war based on
interference from others' in internal affairs. They argue that
such adventurous actions could bring a lasting negative impact to
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian Democratic Forum in the ruling coalition Tuesday
also expressed opposition to NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, ethnic Hungarians living in the autonomous region
of Vojvodina, Yugoslavia, dispatched representatives to meet the
Hungarian Political State Secretary in a southern city of Szeged.
</P>
<P>
They urged Hungary to proceed from the interests of ethnic
Hungarians abroad and reject NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
Amid the disagreeing voices, the Hungarian Ministry of Foreign
Affairs Tuesday reiterated its "extreme hope" for a peaceful
settlement to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
