<HEADLINE> One Million US Dollar Note Seized in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- An one million U.S. dollar
currency note was seized Tuesday by the Sri Lankan police,
according to the official newspaper Daily News Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The one million U.S. dollar note was seized in an under cover
operation by the Terrorist Investigation Division (TID) officers
posing as businessmen, police sources told the paper.
</P>
<P>
Following a tip-off TID detectives had contacted a Muslim
businessman, a broker who wanted to negotiate the sale of the one
million dollar note for 60 million rupees at a hotel in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
From there, they were taken to a private house in the city
where they were introduced to the Muslim businessman's father and
a young Tamil who produced the note.
</P>
<P>
At this point, the detectives pounced on the suspect, recovered
the note and arrested all three suspects.
</P>
<P>
Investigations reveal that the Tamil suspect had paid several
visits to India and if he failed to sell the note in Sri Lanka he
intended to travel to Singapore to sell it, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources believed that the money was to be used to finance
Sri Lanka's rebel Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
A similar note for one million U.S. dollars was recovered by
police last week from a woman at Chilaw, North of Colombo, who was
married to an Indian and had spent the past eight years there,
said the sources, adding that Police are investigating whether
there was a connection between the two holders of the currency
notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
