<HEADLINE> France to Participate in OSCE Mission to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- France will participate in an
observation mission of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to Serbia's secessionist province of
Kosovo, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign and Defense ministries are working on conditions to
take part in the OSCE mission aiming to verify on the ground
Belgrade's compliance with the United Nations resolution, Vedrine
told parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement secured by U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic earlier Tuesday, the
OSCE is to send a 2,000-strong mission to Kosovo to ensure the
implementation of the peace accord there.
</P>
<P>
The deal was hammered out amid threats of imminent military
intervention from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
which issued a 96-hour ultimatum to Milosevic to comply with the
U.N. resolution or face air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine described the deal as "very important" but urged that
"the details of this agreement must now be filled out" and that
the U.N. Security Council should approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO should also organize verification in the air
besides the one on the ground and urged NATO and Belgrade to reach
such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
He asked Milosevic to make a unilateral statement affirming his
commitment to a political settlement of the Kosovo conflicts
through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister also called for an early meeting of
the six-nation Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, which comprises
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
