<HEADLINE> New Body Set up to Protect Women From Violence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
formed a Commission on Violence Against Women to curb violence
against women, national newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A presidential decree setting up the 21-member commission was
signed by President B.J. Habibie on October 9.
</P>
<P>
Members of the commission include noted psychologist Saparinah
Sadli and businesswomen Herawati Diah.
</P>
<P>
Saparinah told reporters that the commission is in accordance
with the government's 1984 ratification of an UN declaration on
violence against women.
</P>
<P>
The commission's mission was to remind the government to
continue efforts aimed at "a conducive situation" for the
realization of human rights, particularly when women were
concerned, she added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that members of the commission voiced doubt
that last Friday's slaying of rape counselor Martadinata, better
known as Ita, was a "criminally motivated murder".
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old victim was found with her neck slashed and stab
wounds on her hands, abdomen and chest at her Central Jakarta
House on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Saparinah said Ita's death was a result of ongoing threats
against women investigating rapes that occurred during the May
riots. The murder and accompanying misinformation was allegedly
carried out by "government-backed perpetrators".
</P>
<P>
The country saw the worst looting and rioting in decades in
Jakarta and other cities from May 13 to 15. About 1,200 lives were
claimed, and thousands of buildings and vehicles were damaged and
burnt. Activists have reported that 168 women were gang-raped or
otherwise sexually assaulted during the riots and 20 of them died
or committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
"The terrorism against the activists would be difficult to
prove, but what happened to Ita clearly proves that threats were
inflicted on the group," Saparinah said.
</P>
<P>
She also criticized government officials for doubting reports
that dozens of ethnic Chinese women were raped and sexually
assaulted.
</P>
<P>
"The president has strongly condemned the rapes and assaults as
barbaric acts... so these officials should follow what has
previously been said. They should admit massive cases of rapes did
occur during the riots," she added.
</P>
<P>
National Police Chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi said in August that
some non-governmental organizations were exaggerating reports of
rapes and sexual assaults against Chinese-Indonesian women during
the riots.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces (ABRI) Commander Gen. Wiranto has also
repeatedly said that ABRI had found no evidence to substantiate
the claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
