<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President Asks Prodi to Seek Backing for New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro on Tuesday asked caretaker Prime Minister Romano Prodi to
examine the possibility of forming a new coalition coalition, four
days after Prodi resigned amid a confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a "partial mandate" to Prodi, the president charged him to
"examine the existence of parliamentary support which would permit
the formation of a new government".
</P>
<P>
He asked Prodi to report his findings as soon as possible to
provide the basis for a full mandate and put an early end to the
government crisis over the controversial 1999 budget bill.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro said he decided to give the partial mandate to Prodi
following suggestions by several party leaders during political
consultations in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said after accepting the mandate that he would "get down
to work immediately" in order to report the result to the
president as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The center-left government led by Prodi's Olive Tree Party
resigned last Friday after losing a confidence vote in the lower
house by just one vote.
</P>
<P>
The confidence vote was called because the Communist
Refoundation Party, which had supported Prodi since the 1996
election, decided to withdraw its crucial backing from the
government's draft 1999 budget announced on September 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
