<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec Premier Calls on Election in Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard
said Tuesday that the French-speaking province of Canada will hold
a general election this fall.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard made the announcement Tuesday while touring the Lower
St. Lawrence region, reports said.
</P>
<P>
"When you've been in power for more than four years, you find
yourself up against the wall and you come across as a condemned
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The election, which he must call before September 1999, "will
be in the fall," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Bouchard stopped short of saying what date the election
will be held. November 23 or November 30 is considered by many as
the likeliest date.
</P>
<P>
Recent poll shows that Quebec could have a very tight election
race if a general election was called this fall.
</P>
<P>
Quebec's main opposition Liberal Party leads the ruling Parti
Quebecois by about four percentage points, but there remains a
high level of satisfaction with the Parti Quebecois government,
the poll said.
</P>
<P>
That situation could favor Parti Quebecois. The support for
the Liberals is concentrated on a few areas, such as Montreal,
where the number of seats up for grabs is limited.
</P>
<P>
In the election four years ago, Parti Quebecois defeated the
Liberals by nearly 30 seats in the fight for the 125-seat
provincial legislature. Less than one percentage point divided
the two parties in popular support.
</P>
<P>
If the ruling party wins the upcoming election, another
referendum on Quebec's separation from Canada could be held if
Bouchard deems it winnable, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
