<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Launches Projects to Prevent Soil Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central
China will spend more than 2.5 billion yuan (about three million
U.S. dollars) to launch the largest soil erosion control project
since 1949 in the wake of this summer's devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
About 44,000 square kilometers of the province's land area are
suffering from soil erosion due to the deterioration of the
ecological surroundings along the province's four rivers: the
Xiangjiang, Zijiang, Yuanshui, and Lishui, out of which more than
30 million tons of sand flow annually into Dongting Lake.
</P>
<P>
As fundamental steps to deal with the problem, the provincial
government decided to undertake large-scale soil and water
resources protection projects and the improvement of ecological
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the province will expand its forest
coverage rate to 55 percent in five years, and will launch a group
of projects including forest protection, afforestation and the
restoration of grasslands.
</P>
<P>
Logging will be prohibited on about 78,000 hectares of the
province's forests, and passes to three million hectares of
forests in river and lake valleys and reservoirs will be sealed
off for cultivation at the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
About 40,000 hectares of farmland will be restored to forests
each year, and the province plans to spend 40 million yuan (about
five million U.S. dollars) on cultivating 20,000 hectares of
anti-flood forests and 330,000 hectares of grasslands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Draws Over 7 Bln Dollars' Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Myanmar
reached 7.064 billion U.S. dollars at the end of March this year,
according to a latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The investment, that came from 23 countries and regions, covers
303 projects.
</P>
<P>
Of the projects, those in oil and gas sector drew the largest
amount of investment, reaching 2.303 billion dollars, followed by
manufacturing, hotels and tourism, real estate and mining.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that Singapore ranked the first among
foreign investors, injecting into the country 1.485 billion
dollars, followed by Britain, Thailand, Malaysia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar adopted an open-door market-oriented economic
policy in late 1988, investment environment gradually improved
with foreign investors stepping in.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the impact of the Asian financial crisis,
Myanmar received only 1.3 billion dollars of foreign investment in
1997, one billion dollars less than that in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country drew 222 million dollars of foreign investment in
the first six months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
