<HEADLINE> Slovenian President Cautious with US-Yugoslav Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Slovenian President
Milan Kucan said here Tuesday that the Holbrooke-Milosevic
agreement should be carefully and cautiously evaluated.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after he met Polish President
Aleksander Kwasniewski, the Slovenian president said it still
remains a question whether the Yugoslav president has agreed to
the autonomy of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and the access of
OSCE (Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe)
observers to the area.
</P>
<P>
Whether Milosevic's compromise was made just to avoid a NATO
military intervention also remains a question, he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the Kosovo issue should be permanently
settled and the conditions set by the Contact Group should be met.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement negotiated between U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the OSCE will
deploy 2,000 observers to verify compliance with UN demands that
include an immediate ceasefire, a withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo, a return of refugees, and autonomy talks with ethnic
Albanians. 
</P>
