<HEADLINE> Small Delegation Have Big Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Although there are only six
members in the Russian delegation -- a team leader, a coach and
four girl athletes -- they have high hopes for gold medals at the
International Schoolsports Federation (ISF) World Gymnasiade s
tarting here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
All the four girls will take part in the rhythmic gymnastics
competitions. Team leader Turcisbekova said the group was
carefully selected.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the girls have participated in an
international event, but they are confident of doing well.
</P>
<P>
The delegation came here earlier after a three-day journey in
the train from a city nearby Lake Baikal.
</P>
<P>
The first thing they asked for on their arrival was to have a
training hall. As there is no gymnasium near their hotel, their
demand could not be satisfied at once.
</P>
<P>
But the girls practiced their first-day training on the hotel
corridor's carpet instead. Their embarrassment was short-lived
as, the next morning, a more appropriate training ground was
found.
</P>
<P>
In the Russian delegation, it's a family affair story since
three members are from the same family. Sinevesc Marina, the
coach, is also the mother of 8-year-old Turusbekova Veronika, the
youngest athlete in the team, while the team leader is her aunt.
</P>
<P>
"Our whole family loves gymnastics," Irina said. Veronika is
only a second grader but she has been training in gymnastics for
four years and has won a prize at a competition held in Northeast
China.
</P>
<P>
Veronika can only show her performances but will be unable to w
in a medal since she is too young to qualify for the
competition. 
