<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Unemployment Situation Worsening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China is facing severe
unemployment and must rely on labor-intensive projects to
alleviate the situation, according to the China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
China has an unemployed population of between 13-15 million
people and the unemployment rate is eight percent this year. These
figures could climb to 15-18 million, and around nine percent in
1999, the newspaper quoted Dr. Hu Angang of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences as saying.
</P>
<P>
"As the average household has 3.3 persons, as many as 50
million people are affected by unemployment," said Dr. Hu at a
recent economic seminar.
</P>
<P>
The calculation does not include those rural migrants who are
unemployed in the cities. The number of rural surplus laborers was
estimated at 160 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"We can clearly say that China has entered the high
unemployment phase," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, China now supports 26.3 percent of the
world's population with less than four percent of the world's
capital resources.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Hu explained that China saw a sudden outbreak of
unemployment in 1993, when China redoubled its efforts to transfer
from a planned economy to the socialist market economy and
restructure its economy.
</P>
<P>
The old industrial base such as northeast China, whose heavy
industry developed with Soviet aid in the 1950s, and traditional
sectors like transportation and the textile industry, saw the
highest rate of lay-offs.
</P>
<P>
The economist said that China should use its rich labor
resources to the full and put more emphasis on developing
labor-intensive projects to solve the unemployment problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that the development of the private sector will also
help absorb laid-off workers from state-owned enterprises, and
stressed the building of a social security system to ensure a
stable society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Welcomes Political Efforts for Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government warned
on Tuesday that the international community must keep up the
pressure on Yugoslavia to guarantee a peaceful settlement of the
Kosovo conflict, the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Commitments by the United States, NATO (North Atlantic Treaty
Organization) and other international organizations have proved to
be effective, said ministry spokesman Sokol Gjoka.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into consideration that the Belgrade government has not
kept its promises so far, we think it is necessary to exert a
constant political and military pressure on it until resolution
1199 of the UN Security Council is implemented," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We support all the steps taken by the international community
to provide a durable and long-term solution of the Kosovo crisis,
which respects the will of the Kosovo Albanians and international
principles, and which also serves security and stability in the
Balkans," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Gjoka said he hoped that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic would not break his promises after an agreement
early Tuesday with U.S. Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke to
withdraw troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He also urged NATO to carry out its threat of air strikes
against Serbian strategic positions if Serb security forces failed
to withdraw from Kosovo within the 96-hour time limit set by the
alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
