<HEADLINE> Brazil's Trade Deficit With Mercosur Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's trade deficit
with its Southern Common Market (Mercosur) member countries
dropped from 633 million U.S. dollars in the first eight months of
1997 to 327 million dollars in the same period this year.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian official reports said Tuesday that Brazil's exports
to its Mercosur's partners -- Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay --
grew by 6.95 percent to 6.18 billion dollars from January to
August 1998, while its imports rose 1.3 percent from 6.27 billion
dollars in the same period last year to 6.35 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's trade deficit with Argentina amounted to 766
million dollars this year, compared with 1.48 billion dollars in
1997, while its trade surplus with Paraguay went up 52 million
dollars to 558 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But trade deficit with Uruguay increased 28 million dollars.
Brazil exported 577 million dollars worth of products to the
Uruguayan market and imported 696 million in the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
