<HEADLINE> More Than Half of Indonesia's State Firms Unhealthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- More than half of Indonesia's
159 state-owned companies have been categorized as unhealthy, and
more than half of their assets are deemed non-performing, the
Indonesian Observer Wednesday quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Approximately 54 percent of the 159 state firms are unhealthy,
and based on 1997 calculations, state firms could only book a
profit of only 2.61 percent," State Enterprises Minister Tanri
Abeng told a meeting of parliamentarians here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abeng said assets of the state companies totaled 461 trillion
rupiah (46.1 billion U.S. dollars) with more than half being
deposited with state banks or state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
Half of the assets are not non-productive, bring the value of
performing assets managed by the Ministry, excluding state oil
firm Pertamina, to 250 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"That's the amount of assets managed by the state minister for
the empowerment of state enterprises," Abeng said.
</P>
<P>
These are the conditions that make state firms' competitiveness
very low compared to private companies, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"This is what needs to be empowered," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
