<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired U.S. Officer Charged With Spying for Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A retired U.S. Army
intelligence analyst was charged on Tuesday with spying for
selling Russia top-secret documents and could face a life or death
sentence.
</P>
<P>
David Sheldon Boone, 46, a sergeant who used to analyze
intercepted communications at the Pentagon's super-secret National
Security Agency, was arrested at a hotel near Washington on
Saturday after flying to the United States from Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Boone, who appeared Tuesday before U.S. Magistrate Judge Welton
C. Sewell in Alexandria, Virginia, was charged with espionage,
which carries a maximum penalty of life in prison, or death if
certain conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) officials said Boone,
who retired in 1991 after working on secret codes, thought he was
meeting with a Russian agent about resuming his alleged espionage
activities, but in reality he was meeting with an undercover FBI
agent.
</P>
<P>
Boone told the FBI's fake Russian spy that, during 1988-1991 in
Germany, he sold the Soviets details of U.S. targets for tactical
nuclear weapons in case of a Soviet nuclear attack and a 300-to
400-page handbook listing reconnaissance and intelligence
collection systems used by the U.S. military, according to an FBI
affidavit.
</P>
<P>
Boone also told the fake Russian agent he had volunteered to
spy for the Soviet Union in 1988 when his marriage was breaking up
and he was so short of cash he used the Soviet payments for
ordinary living expenses while serving in the Army in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Boone expressed a willingness to move back to the United States
for a full-time position with the Russians and said he could set
up a business at home as a cover for his activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the criminal complaint, Boone began spying in 1988
after he walked into the Soviet embassy in Washington and
volunteered his services.
</P>
<P>
Boone was driven out of the embassy in a closed van, was
dropped off several blocks away and given a wig and moustache to
use as a disguise for the next meeting, he told the undercover FBI
agent.
</P>
<P>
In all, Boone said he was paid more than 60,000 U.S. dollars
for the highly sensitive top-secret documents he gave the Russian
agents from 1988 to 1991, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
After the initial meeting in the U.S. embassy, Boone allegedly
made arrangements to continue spying when he was reassigned in
1988 to Augsburg, Germany, where the U.S. Army had a field station.
</P>
<P>
After going to Augsburg, Boone had his first meeting with a
Russian agent identified as "Igor," who gave him a secret
communications plan that included emergency meeting and signal
sites.
</P>
<P>
Boone met with the Russian agent four times a year at various
locations along the Rhine River, allegedly giving him documents
about the capabilities and movements of Soviet forces and about
Soviet tactical nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
