<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Philippines Presidents Agree to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and the Philippines
Tuesday night agreed to use their respective currencies in an
effort to enhance bilateral trade and to materialize the plan on
an ASEAN single currency, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesian President B.J. Habibie and Philippine President
Joseph Estrada agreed to use the two countries' currencies in an
effort to step up bilateral economic relations," Alatas was quoted
by Antara News Agency Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alatas was speaking to reporters following a one-on-one meeting
between Habibie and Estrada at the Melia Panorama Hotel on
Indonesia's Batam Island near Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia and the Philippines are exploring the
possibility of making regulations on the financial sector as the
Philippines made such an agreement with Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian countries wish to use an ASEAN single currency
like the European countries had done, Alatas said in the company
of his Philippine counterpart Domingo Siazon.
</P>
<P>
Alatas pointed out that the two presidents also agreed that the
ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) should be implemented earlier, namely
in 2001 instead of 2003.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Habibie would attend the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation Forum (APEC) to take place in Malaysia in November,
Alatas reiterated that no decision has yet been taken about it.
</P>
<P>
"The reason is not the current situation in Malaysia, but that
Indonesia has no vice president yet. Even if President Habibie
attends the APEC meeting, he may leave in the morning and return
home in the afternoon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Siazon told reporters that Estrada would attend the meeting as
APEC is important for the Philippines and for ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia is the host so we have committed to be present,"
Siazon added.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Alatas told reporters that Habibie and Estrada
also expressed concern over the situation in Malaysia and
expressed the sincere hope that this present situation can be
quickly overcome by the Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
"We do not interfere other sovereign countries. We do not tell
each other what to do with regard to internal developments,"
Alatas added.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for them to meet personally as new
presidents of their respective countries. Estrada took office on
June 30 while Habibie was sworn in on May 21 after his predecessor
Soeharto was forced down amid the country's worst economic and
political crisis in decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
