<HEADLINE> NATO Promises Hungary Security for Coordination Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) said it would provide Hungary with security
guarantees in return for helping to coordinate possible air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The guarantees were offered following Hungarian concerns that
they could suffer retaliation from Yugoslavia's military if they
agreed to NATO's request to assist in coordinating air raids
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday NATO made a formal request for approval to use
Hungary's territorial air space for possible attacks against
Yugoslavia, which aroused concerns among Hungarians.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Serbian official said neighboring countries would be
deemed aggressors if it collaborated in whatever form with NATO's
air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian paper, Nepszabadsaq (People's Freedom), said
Tuesday that it learned from the Chairman of the Committee for
Home Defense in the National Assembly Lanyi Zsolt that NATO had
agreed to provide Hungary with an "air security umbrella" and
would deploy fighter jets in the country in the event the use of
its air space incurred military threats from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO's liaison group has reportedly arrived in Budapest to
advise Hungary on coordination plans with the military bloc's
activity. 
