<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Destroy Dikes in Largest Lake for Flood Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China will destroy hundreds of
dikes to increase the flood-water storage capacity of its largest
lake by nearly 25 percent in about three years in an effort to more
effectively control flooding.
</P>
<P>
"The flood water storage area of Poyang Lake will be increased
by 1,137 square kilometers in about three years, and this
increased area is about the same size of the lake lost to land
reclamation over the past four decades," according to an official
of east Jiangxi Province where the lake is located.
</P>
<P>
Poyang Lake, on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, plays
an important role in diverting flood water from the river. The
lake area reached 5,100 square kilometers in the early 1950s, with
a storage capacity of 37 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
However, land reclamation efforts in the past four decades have
reduced the lake area to 3,900 square kilometers and the storage
capacity to 29.8 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
To raise the lake's water storage capacity, all non-essential
dikes in the lake area with a height below 22 meters will be
leveled or destroyed, said Liu Zhengmin, head of the Jiangxi
Provincial Headquarters for Flood Control and Drought Relief.
</P>
<P>
By this standard, a total of 234 dikes will be destroyed,
increasing the lake's flood-water storage capacity by 5.92 billion
cubic meters, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"The past efforts to reclaim land from the lake and build
houses or barriers on the lake have substantially reduced the
lake's capacity to divert and store flood water, and significantly
increased the difficulties of flood control," Liu noted.
</P>
<P>
"The severe flooding this year has taught us a profound
lesson," he added.
</P>
<P>
The months-long flooding of the Yangtze River which began in
mid-June, the worst since 1954, has been partly blamed on
irrational logging of trees in the upper reaches and on land
reclamation. The flooding resulted in grave losses of life and
property.
</P>
<P>
"The flooding has made us deeply realize the importance of
utilizing natural resources reasonably," Liu said. "Even though we
can reap tons of grain from the reclaimed land, our gains are
outweighed by losses when compared with the manpower and materials
used to fight against the floods."
</P>
<P>
Liu's views are widely shared by local officials and residents,
as evidenced by the popular support for the government plan to
destroy dikes and increase the lake area. Implementation of the
plan, which has been sanctioned by the central authorities,
requires the relocation of 468,000 farmers to areas at higher
elevations.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for construction of accommodations for the
resettlement of farmers are proceeding smoothly, according to
Liu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
