<HEADLINE> Cuba's Foreign Minister to Visit U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's Foreign Minister Roberto
Robaina left here Tuesday for the United Nations headquarters in
New York to present a new resolution project condemning the U.S.
blockade of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
At Havana airport, Robaina said that he will present necessary
arguments for the defense of the project, and proceed to travel to
the Portuguese city of Porto, venue for the current Ibero-American
Summit.
</P>
<P>
He said that since 1992, Cuba has been presenting the
resolution proposal, which year after year is gaining support from
the international community.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the Cuban project has to be
presented Wednesday for the first time in the morning, during the
General Assembly's full session, to be voted by midday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Cuban resolution proposal was supported by 143
countries, with 17 abstentions. Only two countries were in favor
of the U.S. blockade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
