<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7th East Asia Economic Summit Put Forth Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Seventh East Asia
Economic Summit Tuesday put forth the Action Plan for Global
Growth and Reform of the World Financial System
</P>
<P>
The plan says participants of the 1998 East Asia Economic
Summit of the World Economic Forum are deeply concerned about the
drift of the world economy and financial markets as well as the
growing risk of global recession, and they believe a string of
strong and bold actions must be taken immediately.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, developed countries, namely the United States,
Canada, European countries and Japan are urged to bolster their
economies and the world economy against the rising threat of
global recession, immediately expand the provision of official
loans and credit guarantees to the emerging markets in crisis,
especially to cover basic necessities in foodstuffs, energy and
medical and pharmaceutical supplies, and to reconfirm their
commitment to open trade in goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries are warned to abstain from allowing an
arbitrary use of "safeguards" such as anti-dumping measures or
countervailing duties to become protectionist policies in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Japan has a GNP twice as large as all of the rest
of Asia combined, it says Japan has a special responsibility to
help the region emerge from its current deep recession.
</P>
<P>
Japan is urged to undertake strong and further measures to
further expand its money supply, to recapitalize its financial
sector, to ensure speedy recovery of the banking sector and adopt
a dynamic, growth promoting fiscal policy with emphasis on
expanding domestic consumption, and to implement the
lately-announced plan of 30 billion U.S. dollars in Japanese
assistance to the crisis countries of East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Canada and European countries are urged to
adopt significant cuts in interest rates, to facilitate
restructuring by supporting realistic settlements on the foreign
debt owed by Asian corporations to international creditors.
</P>
<P>
Governments in the crisis countries are urged to remain
committed to maintaining open markets for goods and services as
well as foreign investment, to continuing the effort towards
greater transparency and to the strengthening of the institutional
infrastructure to support open market, to accelerate the
recapitalization of the financial and banking sectors, to
facilitate the rapid restructuring of corporate debt in a
pragmatic manner, and to review the prudent limits on short term
capital inflows, including limits on short-term foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Regarding a reform of the world financial system, the plan says
that G-7 economies should undertake to establish a new regulatory
regime for the monitoring, disclosure, and regulation of highly
leveraged short-term flows, as well as off-balance-sheet
commitments and derivative transactions.
</P>
<P>
It stresses the need for a comprehensive reconsideration by the
membership of the IMF and the World Bank of the mandate,
structures, functions and resources of these institutions.
</P>
<P>
It also says the participants endorse proposals for an
emergency" Global Growth Summit" and stress strongly that the
emerging market economies should be equally represented along with
the advanced economies at such summit.
</P>
<P>
It says at the end that these measures would constitute a
critical step towards a renewal of world growth, which is now the
critical condition to stabilizing emerging economies and world
markets.
</P>
<P>
They would also set the basis for the establishment of a new
global financial architecture, it adds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
