<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council will on Wednesday
resume consultations on Angola and discuss a draft resolution on
the possible extension of the mandate of the U.N. Observer Mission
in Angola (MONUA), Jeremy Greenstock, the council president, said
on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came at the end of the council's consultations on
Angola, at which Issa Diallo, special representative of the U.N.
secretary-general for Angola, briefed the 15 Security Council
members on the current situation in the African country.
(UN-Angola)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)
reiterated on Tuesday that it has not found any evidence that Iraq
possesses nuclear weapons, while insisting on being given free and
full access to new inspection sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's nuclear weapons related assets have been destroyed,
removed or rendered harmless and the related infrastructure is
under ongoing monitoring and verification (OMV), IAEA Director
General Mohamed Elbaradei told the U.N. Security Council.
(IAEA-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Serbian government on Tuesday fully endorsed
the accord reached earlier in the day by Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke to
ease the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which allows 2,000-strong force of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe to monitor the situation in
Serbia's southern province of Kosovo, was endorsed at a special
session of the Serbian cabinet chaired by Prime Minister Mirko
Marjanovic, according to a statement issued by the Serbian
Information Ministry. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran stated Tuesday that the Afghan Taliban must be
punished if the U.N. special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi failed in his
mission to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, deputy foreign
minister for Asia-Pacific affairs Mohsen Aminzadeh made the remark
on the eve of Brahimi's visit to Qandahar, Taliban's headquarters
in southern Afghanistan. (Iran-Taliban-Brahimi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic said on
Tuesday an agreement was a "lasting basis for a solution" to the
crisis of Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued from Milosevic's office said a constructive
approach "has been shown that can indubitably represent the
lasting basis for a political solution of autonomy for Kosovo
within Serbia." (Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi leaders made no decision on whether to resume
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors at their meeting Tuesday,
the official Iraqi News Agency reported. (Iraq-UNSCOM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- The third round of Burundi peace talks opened
Tuesday in north Tanzania's Arusha town with conflicting parties
having a general debate of democracy in the central Africa
country. (Burundi-Peace-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council of the United Nations
Monday once again called on Iraq to reverse its decision and
resume full cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors.
(UN-Iraq-Weapons) 
</P>
