<HEADLINE> Hoddle Up-beat on England's Chances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- England manager Glenn Hoddle
was in an up-beat mood ahead of Wednesday's vital clash in
Luxembourg despite a disappointing goalless draw with Bulgaria at
the European Soccer Championship qualifying match last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said in a press conference on Tuesday: "We have let
ourselves down over these last two matches against Sweden and
Bulgaria but we have got to address that - and we can start by
winning tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"That will put us in a better position for when we resume our
campaign in March," he added.
</P>
<P>
England have three injury worries ahead of the encounter in
the form of Graeme Le Saux (foot), Teddy Sheringham (calf) and
Sol Campbell (knee).
</P>
<P>
With Andy Hinchcliffe already out of contention through
injury, Le Saux's injury is of most concern - and if he is ruled
out, then Manchester United's Phil Neville is the obvious
candidate to fill in the left wing-back role.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle said: "Le Saux and Sheringham are unlikely to train
tonight. We are hoping that Sol will be okay to join in and I
would say the other two are more of a doubt ahead of tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Hoddle also told Paul Gascoigne that he can still have a
future with England if he wins his battle to overcome his drink
problem.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle said: "A lot of people have tried to help Paul
Gascoigne in the past but this is the first step in him trying to
address the situation himself. I think that's a good and positive
sign for him.
</P>
<P>
"As regards playing for England again, the door has always
been left open for Paul Gascoigne if he can regain his top form,
" he added. 
</P>
