<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Cloned Calves Born in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Ten cloned heifer calves
have been born at AgResearch's Ruakura Center near Hamilton in
central-western North Island of New Zealand, the New Zealand Press
Association (NZPA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local scientists believe this is the biggest set of identical
animals cloned from a single adult.
</P>
<P>
The cloned calves are all genetically identical to each other
and to their four-year-old mother. They are distinguishable by
their different black and white markings.
</P>
<P>
NZPA quoted AgResearch scientist David Wells as saying the
calves were all cloned of a high-performing Friesian dairy cow.
They were produced in a laboratory using somatic cell nuclear
transfer, the process that produced Dolly the sheep, the world's
first cloned animal, in which an adult cell was fused with an egg.
</P>
<P>
Ruakura's cloning team, led by Dr. Wells, was the second in the
world to produce a cloned lamb.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wells said the research now focuses on identifying factors
that affect the efficiency of the cloning process.
</P>
<P>
"The process of cloning from adult cells is still very much an
experimental one in a number of areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The work now aims at increasing the number of successful
pregnancies from cloned embryos, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
