<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand To Boost Off-Shore Tourism Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 12.5 million New
Zealand dollars (6.6 million U.S. dollars) would be pumped next
year into promoting New Zealand as a tourist destination for the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
In a series of tourism promotion plans, which were released
here Wednesday, New Zealand Tourism Minister Murray McCully said
New Zealanders are in danger of being "too slow to recognize the
opportunities springing from millennium events planned for the
next 18 months".
</P>
<P>
The events include next year's APEC meetings and the America's
Cup, and the Golf World Cup next month.
</P>
<P>
They would attract millions of viewers and international media
attention, McCully stressed.
</P>
<P>
The extra funding is a "recognition that New Zealand will enjoy
international branding and profiling opportunities next year, the
like of which we will not see for several decades", he said.
</P>
<P>
McCully said the New Zealand Government plans to use the
tourism money to draw in 1.54 million visitors, up eight percent
over this year's likely arrivals, and 3.5 billion NZ dollars
(1.85 billion U.S. dollars) in tourism earnings (excluding
airfares), up 11 percent on the 1998 forecast.
</P>
<P>
According to the tourism minister, the additional funding
announced today will substantially be spent in New Zealand's three
traditional markets of North America, Australia and Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
