<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Introduce Resolution on Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council will on Wednesday resume consultations on Angola and
discuss a draft resolution on the possible extension of the
mandate of the U.N. Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA), Jeremy
Greenstock, the council president, said on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came at the end of the council's consultations on
Angola, at which Issa Diallo, special representative of the U.N.
secretary-general for Angola, briefed the 15 Security Council
members on the current situation in the African country.
</P>
<P>
"The council expresses warm support for the special
representative in taking forward his mission in Angola in what a
really quite difficult circumstance at present," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to discuss a proposal put
forward by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to extend the mandate
of MONUA for up to six weeks, so that his special representative
could have more chances to contact all parties concerned in order
to avert another war in the country.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that Angolan Government recently threatened to cut
off all contacts with the U.N. special representative if he
continued to deal with Jonas Savimbi, head of the rebel UNITA, who
was disqualified by the Government for the partership in the
political dialogue under the 1994 Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Angola was plunged into a civil war shortly after its
independence in 1975. The international community has blamed
Savimbi and the UNITA leadership for stalling the peace process.
</P>
<P>
MONUA comprises 725 military personnel and 388 civilian police
observers, compared with a U.N. presence of more than 7,000 in the
early phase of the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
