<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- European bourses closed mixed on
Tuesday after a fading two-day rally, while the soft U.S. dollar
was proving a burden to sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Traders in the London market were unable to resist taking
profits from yesterday's record points gain in the FTSE 100, as
weaker international markets unhinged sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 ended the day down 47 at 4990, on robust volume of
986m shares traded.
</P>
<P>
The index attempted a dramatic recovery from the early
Asian-inspired weakness, only to be undone by a nervous session on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Dow finished well off its best in yesterday's session,
which combined with a steep reverse in Tokyo, to force a swift
session low in London of 4956, as yesterday's 214-point surge was
soon forgotten.
</P>
<P>
The index started to come back to life amid solid index futures
and news that underlying inflation had hit the government's target
for the second month running in September. But the FTSE's battle
to hold above the 5000-level was lost as the Dow was unable to
stay above 8000.
</P>
<P>
"We saw some profit-taking when the index moved above 5000
today," one trader said. "Things seem to have settled down, but
its really just guesswork how the international markets are going
to perform."
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares finished marginally higher,
reflecting investors' worries about a weak dollar.
</P>
<P>
The leading Dax index finished 49 higher at 4,274 although the
electronically-traded Xetra Dax closed slightly down. Yesterday,
the Xetra Dax posted the sharpest increase in its one-year
history, gaining 298 points, or 7.5 percent at the close.
</P>
<P>
Early-session profit-taking coupled with fears of a stronger
Deutschmark had sparked off some sharp early weakness in the
leading index.
</P>
<P>
The market's partial recovery at midday was connected to a
slight rebound in the value of the dollar. Domestic "haven" shares
gained on the loss of dollar-sensitive stocks like those in the
car and chemicals sectors.
</P>
<P>
Energy concerns also posted technical gains on the back of
their recent underperformance.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stock prices recovered from earlier losses as
investors went bargain hunting. The leading Cac 40 index finished
up 15 points at 3,279.
</P>
<P>
"French stocks are holding up well after the recent rises,"
said a trader at a Japanese brokerage house in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose yesterday on the back of positive news from Japan
and global efforts toward resolving hedge-fund problems. But
stocks had fallen earlier today on profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
"The CAC should remain between 3050 and 3400 within the next
two weeks," said a trader at a French brokerage house. "The
direction of the French stock market will depend on Japan and the
U.S." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Ceasefire in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Tuesday urged a cessation of all military activity
in East Timor and a substantial reduction of the Indonesian
military presence in the Territory.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by his spokesman said he was concerned by
the rising tensions there and was particularly "disturbed by
reports of armed clashes in the Territory" and by remarks of local
officials to provoke large-scale protests in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General would like to underline that, in view of
the important opportunities that have been created for a resolution
of the question of East Timor through the negotiations under his
auspices...it is incumbent on all parties concerned to avoid
taking steps that could jeopardize or unnecessarily complicate
the delicate efforts to find a just settlement to this long
running dispute," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Annan "intends to further intensify his consultations with East
Timorese leaders with a view to enduring their active involvement
in the negotiating process," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
East Timor with a population of 800, 000 and an area of 18,889
square kilometers has been a dispute between Indonesia and
Portugal since 1975 and the U.N. has been seeking a just,
comprehensive and internationally-acceptable solution to the
question.
</P>
<P>
Annan brokered a dialogue on the autonomy of the Territory
between Indonesia, Portugal and his personal representative in
August, and talks between the parties are continuing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Presses Yugoslavia to Make Serious Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
pressed Yugoslavia to make "serious progress" towards the end of
the Kosovo crisis within four days as a condition to avoid air
strikes from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton told reporters on Tuesday that
there was a good chance of averting NATO air strikes against
Yugoslav military targets, but it all depended on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"We prefer compliance over conflict, and we hope that will be
the case, but whether it is or not is entirely up to him now,"
Clinton said a day after NATO decided to give Yugoslavia four days
for complying with U.N. demands to avoid air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
Milosevic must make immediate moves toward complying with U.N.
demands on stopping a Serb offensive against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Berger said Milosevic must maintain an 11-day ceasefire,
withdraw the Serb forces from Kosovo and allow a team of 2,000
international observers into Kosovo and cooperate with it so it
can verify Serb compliance.
</P>
<P>
He also said humanitarian agencies must be allowed in to care
for the refugees and see that they are on their way home. And a
timetable for negotiations with Kosovo Albanians on their demands
for autonomy must be established.
</P>
<P>
However, he noticed that all these could hardly be done within
four days. "Obviously, not all these things are going to be
accomplished in 96 hours," said Berger. "We want to see serious
progress toward compliance."
</P>
<P>
Berger said Serb compliance will be monitored from the air by a
system of NATO reconnaissance planes and from land by 2,000
unarmed observers including Americans.
</P>
<P>
He said the observer force would begin to be formed soon and a
leader of the force could be named later on Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981014.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbian Govt Endorses Kosovo Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian government on
Tuesday fully endorsed the accord reached earlier in the day by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. special envoy
Richard Holbrooke to ease the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which allows 2,000-strong force of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe to monitor the situation in
Serbia's southern province of Kosovo, was endorsed at a special
session of the Serbian cabinet chaired by Prime Minister Mirko
Marjanovic, according to a statement issued by the Serbian
Information Ministry.
</P>
<P>
It said the Serbian government believed the agreement has
"fully preserved the territorial integrity and sovereignty of the
country, averted a conflict and lay the conditions for a political
dialogue" on the basis of legal systems of the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the deal, finally hammered out after
nine-day intensive negotiations, was based on the principles that
"political approach and a peaceful solution of problems in Kosovo
achieved through dialogue are the only acceptable means for
reaching settlement on all issues.
</P>
<P>
It said one of the principles was that any solution for Kosovo
issue must respect the territorial integrity and sovereignty and
internationally recognized boundaries of Yugoslavia, which is
formed by the two remaining republics of the former Yugoslavia --
Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
Under the principle of full respect of equality of all citizens
and national communities in Kosovo, citizens in Kosovo shall
govern themselves democratically through assemblies, executive and
judicial organs of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Free and fair elections for Kosovo authorities, including
those on the communal level, will be held within nine months and
the Yugoslav government invites the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to supervise those elections to ensure their
openness and fairness," the Serbian government statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police force under local direction will be
established, to be formed by representative of local population
and coordinated by Kosovo administrative authority, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
