<HEADLINE> U.S. Venture Capital Investments in Internet Hit Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Silicon Valley remains the
No. 1 attraction for U.S. venture capital, receiving over half of
Internet investments during the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
U.S. venture capital investments in Internet-related companies
hit a record 887 million dollars in 164 companies in the quarter,
up 42 percent over the period a year ago, according to a new
survey announced Tuesday by PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC), one of
the world's largest professional services organizations. The
survey covered 500 venture capital firms in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Silicon Valley companies received 55 percent of the money, with
487 million dollars invested in 97 deals. New England was next
with 218 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that size of the deals continued to grow.
During the first half of this year, the top ten Internet-related
venture capital investments each surpassed 20 million dollars, as
an increasing number of investments shifted from early stage
companies to expansion and later stage companies.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.35 billion dollars were invested in the first half
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Internet investments were made in early and
expansion stage companies during the second quarter. But the
investments in early stage companies declined from 48 percent in
1997 to 37 percent in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Internet companies specializing in services
accounted for the largest share of the investments in the first
six months of this year, with 455 million dollars or 34 percent of
the total. Next came software, 31 percent, and
access/infrastructure, 29 percent. PwC said that investments in
Internet service companies should continue to increase as more
businesses begin to take advantage of the explosion in e-commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
