<HEADLINE> IAEA Pursues Free Access to Inspection Sites in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA) reiterated on Tuesday that it has not found
any evidence that Iraq possesses nuclear weapons, while insisting
on being given free and full access to new inspection sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's nuclear weapons related assets have been destroyed,
removed or rendered harmless and the related infrastructure is
under ongoing monitoring and verification (OMV), IAEA Director
General Mohamed Elbaradei told the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
There are no indications that Iraq has any practical capability
for the production of weapon-usable nuclear material in quantities
of any practical significance, he said when briefing the council
on the progress of OMV in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
Available information also provides no indication that Iraq has
assembled nuclear weapons with or without fissile cores, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Elbaradei said, "there is an inevitable degree of
uncertainty in the technically coherent picture that has evolved
of Iraq's clandestine nuclear program".
</P>
<P>
The IAEA sees "a few outstanding questions and concerns" which
need to be resolved, although they "do not either individually or
collectively provide any impediment to the full implementation of
the Agency's OMV plan", he said.
</P>
<P>
He listed them as:
</P>
<P>
-- the status of the nuclear weapon design in April 1991,
including the provision of engineering drawings and models, and
the provision of centrifuge drawings obtained rom foreign
assistance,
</P>
<P>
-- the extent of external assistance to the clandestine nuclear
program,
</P>
<P>
-- the timing and modalities of Iraq's abandonment of its
clandestine nuclear program including the adoption of the
necessary penal laws.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA head said the Agency's current inability to inspect
new sites "seriously weakens" a "vital component of the Agency's
OMV plan".
</P>
<P>
Certification by the IAEA that all Iraq's nuclear weapons have
been accounted for and cannot be rebuilt is a requirement for any
easing or lifting of U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq since its 1990
invasion of kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
