<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Ruling Parties Hail Accord on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Socialist Party of Serbia
(SPS) and the Yugoslav Left (JUL) party on Tuesday fully backed an
accord reached earlier in the day on a peaceful solution to the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The accord, struck by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
U.S. special envoy Richar Holbrooke, allows a 2,000-strong force
of OSCE (Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe) to
ensure the compliance of U.N. resolutions, thus averting an
imminent air strike threatened by NATO.
</P>
<P>
It was "a victory of a principled and well-founded policy"
pursued by President Milosevic, said a joint statement with JUL by
the press office of the SPS, the ruling party of the country.
</P>
<P>
It said the agreement removed the threat of military
intervention against Yugoslavia and enabled the defense of the
country's territorial integrity and independence.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, local ethnic Albanians, who account for 90
percent of 2 million population in Kosovo, shall enjoy autonomy
within Serbia, which forms the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia with
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
"The constructive policy pursued so far is the basis of a
lasting political solution to the autonomy of Kosovo within Serbia
in line with the principles of equality of all the people in the
province," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
