<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2115 GMT, October 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- About 21,000 Palestinian workers are allowed to
enter Israel as of Tuesday after the Israeli army eased a 10-day
closure on Gaza and the West Bank and lifted a curfew on downtown
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The blockade was eased early Tuesday morning, several hours
after the nine-day Jewish holiday of Sukkot, a holiday to
celebrate harvest and commemorate the days the God led Israelis
out of Egypt in ancient times, ended.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army sealed off Gaza and the West Bank last month
following the threats by Islamic Resistence Movement (Hamas) to
attack Israel in retaliation of the killing of its two members
by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The closure was eased briefly for several times but re-imposed
before the Sukkot. (BC-Israel-Closure-Lifting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANTALYA -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic said
Tuesday that the current Kosovo issue should be solved through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference after the signing of a joint
declaration of the Balkan summit held here, Bulatovic said that
Yugoslavia is ready to have dialogs with major international
organizations to find a solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of ethenic Albanians who fled the armed
conflicts in the Kosovo region have returned home, Bulatovic
said.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav prime minister also expressed satisfaction with
the outcome of the summit which ended Tuesday, calling it "a
success." (BC-Turkey-Yugoslav PM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran seized more than two tonnes of drugs last week
nationwide, the official news agency IRNA reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted a report issued by the security forces as saying
that during the drug-fighting operations in the country's east,
the security forces seized 1,200 kilograms of opium and 800
kilograms of morphine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the security forces in Tehran confiscated 11
kilograms of heroin and arrested five people, including an Afghan
national in connection with drug trafficking.
(BC-Iran-Drug-Seizure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen arrived in
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, Tuesday to hold talks with top Saudi leaders
on the latest developments in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. diplomatic sources told the Kuwait News Agency that Cohen
will meet with his Saudi counterpart Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz
on both political and military issues after inspecting U.S. troops
at Prince Sultan air base, south of Riyadh where U.S. military
aircraft are based.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the talks between the two defense ministers
will involve Iraq's refusal in August to cooperate with
U.N. inspectors in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction. (BC-Saudi Arabia-Cohen-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANTALYA -- The Balkan leaders Tuesday called for a peaceful
settlement of the Kosovo issue within the framework of the
U.N. Security Council Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration issued at the end of the two-day summit in
the southern Turkish port city of Antalya said that the Kosovo
crisis might spread to neighboring countries if it cannot be
solved as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the Kosovo issue should be politically solved
within the framework of ensuring sovereignty and territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia. (BC-Turkey-Balkan Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli cabinet approved here Tuesday the
appointment of the hawkish Ariel Sharon as foreign minister, the
Prime Minister's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu brought the appointment to
the cabinet for approval and the Knesset (parliament) Speaker Dan
Tichon will announce Sharon's appointment in the plenum later this
week or next week, the office added. (BC-Israel-Sharon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Israeli man was killed and another one
critically injured in a shooting incident Tuesday, Israeli police
said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred near Ora, a communal farm about five
kilometers west of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem police spokesman Shmuel Ben-Ruby said the victims
were bathing in a spring near Ora when shots were fired at
them. The assailants fled the scene after the shooting and their
car was later found abandoned in the southern Jerusalem, near the
border with the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The assailants were Palestinian militants and Israeli police
and soldiers of the defense forces are conducting a manhunt for
the assailants. (BC-Israeli-Shooting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A big explosion rocked a West Bank village
Tuesday, injuring a number of villagers, Palestinian police said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred in the village of Azawiya, about 25
kilometers southwest of the West Bank city of Nablus, the police
added. (BC-Israel-Explosion) 
</P>
</TEXT>
